<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 66 People Killed in Bus Attack in Egypt: TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 66 people, including
foreign tourists and Egyptians, have been reportedly killed in a
terrorist attack in the Upper Egyptian city of Luxur this morning,
according to Egypt state television.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian TV broke off its normal broadcasting to announce
the latest casualties a few hours after unidentified gunmen shot
at a tour bus and fought a two-hour gun battle with police near a
tourist site in Luxor, about 560 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed, this would be the biggest single toll in a
terrorist attack in a wave of violence that swept Egypt over the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Hassan el-Alfi, charged with striking down
Islamic militants fighting a five-year war against President Hosni
Mubarak's secular government, has flown to Luxor.
</P>
<P>
A special plane carrying a medical team landed at Luxor airport
to transport the casualties to Cairo for treatment. Minister of
Health Ismail Sallam also flew there to supervise those injured in
the attack, the second in the country in two months.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier report, the Middle East News Agency said 22 were
wounded, including 11 Egyptians and 11 foreign tourists and two in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
An official statement is expected to be released at any moment
defining the number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian TV in a previous bulletin quoted an official
security source as saying that the six gunmen were all killed.
</P>
<P>
But MENA quoted "a top level security source" in Luxor as
saying that there may be a seventh terrorist still at large.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a security source as saying that the terrorists fired
haphazardly at the tourist bus travelling from a dock on the Nile
to a tourist site in el Deir al Bahari, before they fled in the
direction of the Valley of Queens.
</P>
<P>
In a shoot-out with the police immediately after they opened
fire, one gunman was killed. In the following pursuit of the
remaining five, the police managed to kill them all during the
subsequent exchange of fire, said MENA.
</P>
<P>
According to some tourist guides on site, the bus was carrying
Japanese, American and German tourists when it was hijacked by the
attackers and driven to the Valley of Queens which houses hundreds
of Pharaonic tombs.
</P>
<P>
So far no one has claimed responsibility for the attack. But
speculations have it that the Islamic militants scheming to
install a strict Islamic rule in Egypt with violence were to blame.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,000 have been killed since 1992, mostly policemen,
terrorists, tourists and civilians.
</P>
<P>
As the government's crackdown has largely confined the violence
to such southern hideouts as Assuit and Minya, undeterred foreign
tourists still patron Luxor, a top Egyptian tourist attraction
that boasts mammoth Pharaonic temples and royal tombs.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack targeting foreign tourists, nine Germans
and an Egyptian driver were killed on September 18 in a gunshoot
and firebomb attack on a bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities
Museum in Cairo. The two assailants were sentenced to death on
October 30.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, a vulnerable target of terrorism, has brought about 4
million tourists and 3 billion U.S. dollars to Egypt last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
