<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Leaves for Pakistan After Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright left Saudi Arabia's capital Riyadh today
for Pakistan after her visits to Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait and Saudi
Arabia to rally support for U.S. military build-up in the region.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) quoted diplomatic sources in Riyadh
as saying that during her stay in Saudi Arabia, Albright held
talks with Saudi King Fahd and Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz on the latest developments in the region and the
current standoff between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the ramifications of Iraq's decision to
ban U.S. arms inspectors from taking part in the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to try to persuade Iraq to reverse its decision and
resolve the crisis through diplomacy before resorting to a
military option.
</P>
<P>
They renewed their appeal to Iraq to stop placing obstacles on
the way of the U.N. arms inspection and fully comply with all
U.N. Security Council resolutions to eliminate tension in the
region, the KUNA said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said at the conclusion of her three-hour stay in
Kuwait Sunday that the U.S. was actively pursuing a diplomatic
solution to the crisis, "but if (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein
insists on threatening the wish of the international community, we
cannot rule out other options."
</P>
<P>
She also reiterated the U.S. stand that Saddam Hussein should
allow the U.N. Special Commission inspectors to carry out their
mission regardless of their nationality.
</P>
<P>
She affirmed that "there is no way out for Saddam Hussein if
he doesn't reverse his decision and change course. That is a
message I can clearly say now," which she said was supported and
applauded by the countries she visited.
</P>
<P>
She asserted that Iraq should implement all U.N. resolutions
and rescind from its decision to expel U.S. members in the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expelled six Americans working with the UNSCOM last
Friday, causing other 66 members of the commission to pull out
of the country and a military build-up by the U.S. in the Gulf
for a possible military strike.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the U.S. was looking for a political
solution to the crisis, but she did not rule out other options
if tension continues to escalate.
</P>
<P>
She said the aim of her tour in the Gulf was to caution the
states of the region of the dangers the Iraqi regime is subjecting
the region to.
</P>
<P>
Albright made it clear in Doha Sunday while attending the
opening ceremony of the fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic conference that Washington was determined that Iraq
should not be allowed to block the U.N. mission although her
country was making every effort to end the crisis through
diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state is on a week-long tour of Europe
and South Asia, but the Gulf crisis has made her take a whirlwind
tour to the four Gulf states before resuming her arranged
schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
