<HEADLINE> Palestinians Hold Demonstrations in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A large number of
Palestinians held demonstrations today in the West Bank city of
Bethlehem to show their sympathy for a Palestinian boy who died of
rubber bullet wounds Saturday in a Jerusalem hospital.
</P>
<P>
Nine-year-old Ali Jawarish, who was wounded Tuesday by rubber
bullets fired by Israeli soldiers, was laid rest Sunday in his
hometown of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Around 1,000 local residents participated in his funeral. Ali's
organs were donated by his family to three Israeli children
patients.
</P>
<P>
The march, which started from the Bethlehem University, ended
in front of the house of Ali inside the Ayda Refugee Camp near
Rachel Tomb.
</P>
<P>
"This march was organized to show our sympathy for Ali, but
also to show our solidarity with the Iraqi people and Palestinian
prisoner Ataf Alayan," one of the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Alayan was released several months ago from Israeli prison
under the Oslo Accords signed by Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), but she was rearrested by the Israeli
police about four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Shorterly after her arrest, she went on a hunger strike to
protest against the arrest and her detention without charge by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Ali was shot by rubber bullets within
a range of only 15 to 20 meters while around 30 Palestinian
children between the age of 8 to 12 throwing stones at Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian police said the open fire regulations
concerning rubber bullets prohibit their use at a range closer
than 40 meters and these regulations also explicitly prohibit
shooting rubber bullets at children.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, 275 Palestinian children under the age
of 16 have been killed by Israeli soldiers, of these 69 were
under the age of 12, Palestinian police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
