<HEADLINE> Bonn Admits Diplomat Offering Iraq Top Secret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The German Foreign Ministry today
admitted that a Bonn diplomat had provided Iraq with hundreds of
classified documents during the 1990 Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Martin Erdmann confirmed a report in
the news weekly Der Spiegal that former diplomat Juergen Mohammed
Gietler, 42, had revealed to Iraq "West's complete political and
military counter-measures" before his arrest at the end of August
1990.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence he passed to Iraq included the French
satellite pictures of Israeli missile sites and United States
military plans such as a report on the number of the Stealth
bombers being sent to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
A court in Duesseldorf sentenced Gietler to five years in
prison in May 1991. The trial was classified as a state secret
so that the espionage case would not go public, which was seen as
one of the most embarrassing security and foreign policy lapses in
Germany's post-war history.
</P>
<P>
The Spiegal magazine said the judge feared that on knowing the
case, Washington would reduce the amount of information passed on
to Bonn in the future.
</P>
<P>
The judge was quoted as saying that he believed the
intelligence Gietler handed over to Iraq even influenced the
course of the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
Gietler converted to Islam in Cairo in 1982 and began spying
for Iraq in the beginning of 1990. He came under suspicion in June
1990, but German domestic security officials did not intervene
hoping for catching any accomplices.
</P>
<P>
Gietler is now a businessman in Ghana after spending three
years in prison. He said his espionage career traced to as early
as 1987 and that he had offered Cairo thousands of documents on
Israel and the Middle East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
