<HEADLINE> Iran to Resume Pistachio Exports to Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran will resume pistachio
export to European countries from December 15 after a suspension
of two months, local daily Tehran Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vice chairman of Iran's Chamber of Commerce, Asadollah
Askarowladi, was quoted as saying that the European Common Market
Commission has decided to allow Iran to export pistachio to its
members.
</P>
<P>
Conditions laid down by the commission for granting export
licenses to Iranian pistachio included testing of pistachio upon
entry to Europe in addition to quality assessment by the standard
and hygiene centers in Iran, Askarowladi said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union countries announced to ban the import of
Iranian pistachio on September 9, fearing contamination by
Aflatoxin B1, a carcinogenic substance produced by molds.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran defended the quality of its pistachio, saying
that the export to Europe was not only uncontaminated but also was
the healthiest type.
</P>
<P>
Askarowladi said the European boycott had no impact on the
export of Iranian pistachio. Iran's pistachio produced this year
totaled 70,000 tons and its export volume has not decreased.
</P>
<P>
Pistachio cultivation in Iran is about 300,000 hectares and
the country expected to earn some 400 million dollars from
pistachio exports.
</P>
<P>
Askarowladi also said that Iranian raisins and dates, 100,000
tons of each being exported annually, also would be tested by the
European common market.
</P>
<P>
"Numerous experiments conducted up to now have shown Iran's
products to be safe and free from contamination," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned Over Iraqi-U.S. Stand-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today expressed its
grave concern over the possible military conflict between Iraq
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Turkey has
been in touch with all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
"As a country in this region, Turkey has been monitoring
the development very closely because it is having adverse
effects on us," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
"So it is our sincere wish to see this problem reach a
peaceful conclusion," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Iraq and the U.S. intensified after the
Iraqi government expelled six Americans on U.N. arms inspections
teams on charges of espionage and blocking the lifting of
sanctions against Iraq imposed after its invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Washington has threatened that it might take military actions
against Iraq if Baghdad continues to defy the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question what is Ankara's position on the
latest crisis, Atacanli stressed that " Turkey is not a party
to the conflict."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also said that the Turkish government expects
Baghdad to abide by all U.N. resolutions in order to avoid a
military confrontation with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
On the possible use of southern Turkey's Incirlik air base
by the United States to attack Iraqi targets, Atacanli
reiterated that Turkish Parliament has a final say if Washington
makes such a request.
</P>
<P>
Local TV and newspaper reports said that one U.S. tanker
plane and several fighters had been deployed in the air base
for a possible attack against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli, however, said that all the military movements in
Incirlik air base were taking place within the framework of
"Operation Northern Watch", which is designed to monitor northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Recalling that Turkey suffered a tremendous economic loss of
30 billion U.S. dollars due to the U.N. sanctions on Iraq,
the spokesman said that some ways and means must be sought
to compensate Turkey's loss. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
