<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Danish Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said today that China and Denmark are
free of any major conflicts, and noted the absence of any barriers
preventing the strengthening of friendship and cooperation based
on common interests and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks during a meeting with Friis Arne
Petersen, permanent secretary of state of the Foreign Ministry of
Denmark. "We are fully confident of the relations," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Petersen's visit to China has enabled the two
sides to exchange views on the issues of common concern and has
been highly conducive to promoting bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian recalled that his two previous visits to Denmark left him
with a lasting impression concerning the country's unique culture
and tradition. He also pointed to the fact that Denmark was
amongst the first group of western nations to establish trade ties
and diplomatic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Petersen said the two countries have a long history of
cooperation, and stressed that Denmark is fully prepared to engage
in friendly and constructive dialogue with China on the basis of
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Denmark hopes to enhance bilateral political,
trade and cultural cooperation in advance of the 50 anniversary of
the establishment of diplomatic relations, an event which will
fall in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Petersen conveyed Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg
Petersen's invitation for Qian to visit Denmark. Qian accepted the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Wang Yingfan and Petersen also
joined in consultations on bilateral relations and international
issues of common concern earlier today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
