<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Calls for Extensive Coordination of Malaria Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has called on the international community to step up
coordination of action against malaria, which kills an estimated
1.5 to 2.7 million people each year, according to a WHO press
release here today.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a two-day meeting here last week, experts agreed
that global coordination is essential and vital for the more
efficient use of resources.
</P>
<P>
"The tools are available for malaria control but moving to
large scale implementation requires coordination mechanisms at
global, regional and country levels," said Dr Ralph Henderson, WHO
Assistant Director-General. "Continuing political support for
malaria control is needed to ensure continuity of action and
sustainability of achievements."
</P>
<P>
Steps will be initiated to review the current coordination
mechanisms at global level with a view to identifying options for
improvement which would be discussed by interested parties during
1998, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
300 to 500 million people suffer from malaria today, according
to WHO. It is the most prevalent disease of the poorest rural
areas and produces recurrent infections.
</P>
<P>
In many endemic areas of Africa it is a year-round problem with
a seasonal increase occurring with the onset of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Although primarily a rural disease, malaria has become
increasingly urban and the growth in resistance to antimalarial
drugs has become a major concern in many countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0017 </DOCNO>
