<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestine Agree to Intensify Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jericho, Palestine, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Senior Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators held a special meeting here today, in
which both sides agreed to intensify talks on implementing the
interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli team was headed by Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh
and Foreign Ministry's legal adviser Yaaov Bardugo, and the
Palestinian team led by senior negotiator Saeb Erekat and Hasan
Asfour. The meeting was also attended by United States Counsul
General John Herbst and some heads of the nine negotiating teams.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Erekat said they
listened to reports on the current state of negotiations given by
heads of the negotiating teams. They discussed the outstanding
interim issues including the Gaza airport and harbor as well as
the safe passage between Gaza Strip and West Bank
</P>
<P>
"We will of course report back to our leaders, hoping
that we can proceed forward. It was agreed today that many
of the committees will work intensively until they reach an
agreement," said Erekat.
</P>
<P>
Naveh said today's meeting was convened according to the
agreement reached during the talks early the month between
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen). He echoed
Erekat's statement that both sides reviewed the previous talks
and explored ways of moving forward.
</P>
<P>
"Our intention is that in the coming days, we are going
to intensify the talks of the steering committees in order to
achieve great progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that today's meeting was convened to prepare
for the scheduled meeting between Levy and Mazen Tuesday in
Jericho to formally resume the negotiations of nine interim
committees.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the PNA had different assessments of the outcome of
the Washington talks held under the auspices of U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
While Levy said both sides had agreed to eliminate the
atmosphere of crisis in order to advance future talks, the
Palestinian side insisted the Washington talks have failed due to
Israel's refusal to make concessions on key issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- The Getico Company of Qatar today signed a memorandum
of understanding with the global Holiday Inn Hotels Corporation
on constructing two hotels in the Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
This was signed on the sidelines of the three-day fourth Middle
East and North Africa Economic Conference in Doha, which opened
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum of understanding, the 400-room
hotel will cost more than 40 million U.S. dollars. It also
involves another 100-room hotel.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the two hotels is due to be completed early
in the year 2000, while the two hotels will come into operation by
the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel and Egypt have resumed negotiations on the
establishment of a pipeline that would pump natural gas through
Sinai Peninsula to Israel in a project that Qatar is interested in
financing, today's The Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an Israeli industry source as saying that
Israel has turned its attention once again to the Egyptian offer
of natural gas as other options appear to be receding.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian free trade zones have absorbed about 250
million U.S. dollars foreign investment so far, Morteza Alviri,
advisor to the Iranian president and secretary of the High Council
of Free Trade Zones, announced last week.
</P>
<P>
He said that negotiations are underway for five billion dollars
investments in the free trade zones and an agreement will soon be
signed with India to build a chemical fertilizer plant at an
estimated cost of 330 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A Kuwaiti petrochemical complex which has a
capacity of turning out 650,000 metric tonnes of ethylene, 450,000
metric tonnes of polyethylene and 350,000 metric tonnes of
ethylene glycol per year started operation last week, Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The complex, named Equate, is a joint venture valued at 2
billion U.S. dollars. Each of the U.S. Union Carbide and Kuwaiti
Petrochemical Industries Company owns 45 percent of the
shares, while Kuwaiti Bubyan Petrochemical Company, a private
company, owns 10 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
Union Carbide Corporation Chairman William Joyce said at the
inauguration ceremony that "Equate will be a formidable new
competitor in the rapidly growing markets for polyethylene and
ethylene glycol in Asia, the Middle East and Europe."
</P>
<P>
Raw materials used by the complex are supplied through a
five-kilometer-long pipeline from the Kuwait National Petroleum
Company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riyadh Supports Diplomatic Than Military Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today voiced
support for solving the current crisis between Iraq and the United
States through diplomacy rather than military option.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by Saudi Foreign Ministry at the end
U.S. State Secretary Madelleine Albright's visit to the kingdom,
said Washington is seeking a diplomatic solution and Saudi Arabia
supports this approach.
</P>
<P>
"At a time when the U.N. Security Council is closely following
this matter (the crisis), Saudi Arabia expresses its satisfaction
at the collective desire to give diplomatic efforts every chance
to resolve the present crisis peacefully," the statement read.
</P>
<P>
It said the Saudi government shares the American position that
the issue involved is not between Iraq and the U.S., but rather,
it is an issue between the Security Council and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad expelled six Americans working with the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on monitoring Iraq's disarmament last Friday,
prompting an UNSCOM decision to pull out of other 63 weapons
inspectors accordingly.
</P>
<P>
"The Saudi side praised the unanimous international position
which called for the preservation of the integrity of UNSCOM," it
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It called on Iraq to rescind its decision to expel the
Americans inspectors. "Such response, along with full compliance
with all Security Council resolutions, is the surest way to
lifting the sanctions and alleviating the suffering of the Iraqi
people," it said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, Albright held separate talks with Saudi King
Fahd and Crown Prince Abdallah Bin Abdel Aziz shortly after her
arrival from Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
