<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Seeks to Settle Share in MENA Bank: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Administration will make
considerable efforts to persuade the Congress to approve the
U.S. share in the initial capital of the Middle East-North Africa
(MENA) Bank, a senior U.S. official said here today.
</P>
<P>
American Assistant Secretary of State for Economic Affairs
Stuart Isenstat made the remarks at a press conference this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Isenstat said that his country's share in the bank's capital is
estimated at 52 million U.S. dollars. The bank's capital amounts
to 1.25 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Isenstat is participating in the three-day fourth MENA conomic
conference, which opened here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that MENA Bank is intended to meet the needs
of both the Middle East and North Africa, and that the bank is
designed to achieve three definite objectives, namely, to help the
private sector, to publicize regional projects and to promote
economic dialogue between nations of the region.
</P>
<P>
Isenstat pointed out that the interim working team in charge of
organizing the bank comprises representatives of Japan, Israel,
Egypt, Canada, Italy and the Netherlands, adding that the working
team has completed most of the necessary work for organizing the
Middle East-North Africa Bank.
</P>
<P>
David Danford, coordinator of the MENA Bank - who participated
in the press conference held by Isenstat - said he looked forward
to Saudi Arabia's contribution to the bank's capital, admitting
that Riyadh had relevant reservations in view of the stumbling of
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The decision to establish the bank was made at the third MENA
conference in Cairo last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
