<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Hails Hungarian Referendum Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana today welcomed the positive result of Hungary's referendum
on joining the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
"The support for NATO membership expressed by a high percentage
of those who voted demonstrates the broad support among the
Hungarian people for membership in the alliance," the NATO chief
said.
</P>
<P>
The final result of referendum, held on Sunday with a turnout
of more than half of the eight million electorate, showed that
some 85 percent of the votes were in favor of NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Solana is expecting a confirmation letter from the Hungarian
government to formally expressing its desire to join NATO and its
willingness to meet the membership requirements.
</P>
<P>
Receipt of this letter will mark the formal end of the
accession negotiations and the start of the run-up to the signing
of the accession protocols.
</P>
<P>
The signing will take place during the December 16 ministerial
meeting of the North Atlantic Council, the executive body of the
16-nation military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Of the three countries invited to join NATO, Hungary was the
only one that chose to hold a referendum. The other two invitees
are Poland and the Czech Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
