<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Digital Modems Let Phone Lines Do Double Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. phone companies are
turning out digital modems that create high-speed connection to
the Internet and let people go on line and talk on the phone at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the USA Today, GTE, a major
telecommunications company, will announce today that it is
offering digital subscriber line (DSL) service to large
residential and office buildings in Los Angeles, San Francisco and
Chicago. DSL compresses data over regular copper phone wires.
</P>
<P>
Other companies, including the US West, the SBC Communications,
Bell Atlantic, Ameritech and BellSouth are also testing on the new
product, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Phone companies are trying to keep prices affordable. US West's
service begins at 40 U.S. dollars a month, plus installation and
equipment fees of several hundred dollars. That would be much
cheaper than ISDN service.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that it would still take years to spread the
technology across the nation, which has 175 million phone lines.
</P>
<P>
Digital modems will pose a challenge to cable TV companies,
which offer high-speed cable modems.
</P>
<P>
DSL and cable modems offer more than just speed. They
eliminate the need for separate phone and computer lines and let
people stay on line 24 hours a day for a flat fee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Official Defends DRC Admittance into SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The decision to admit the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) into the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) was to contribute to the political
stability in the country, a SADC official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende said in a statement that the
decision was taken in view of the fact that DRC was a neighbor of
three SADC member states -- Angola, Tanzania and Zambia -- as
well as the fact that it is a potential major economic partner.
</P>
<P>
"Concern was expressed during the meeting regarding the
apparent double standards being applied to the DRC by certain
quarters on the probe into atrocities committed in that country
before the government of President L. Kabila took office," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Of particular concern was that this issue was being made a
pre-condition to assisting the country in the democratization and
reconstruction process," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the international community to adopt a more
positive and progressive attitude toward the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende also deplored the attempted coup in Zambia last month
and commended the Zambian security forces for thwarting it
successfully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Polish President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing met with visiting Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski
here this evening to exchange views on some major projects in
Sino-Polish economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Describing Kwasniewski's present China tour as "very
important," Li said that the Chinese side is pleased with the
outcome of the in-depth talks between Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and President Kwasniewski held this morning.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski told Li that Poland expects a lot on his current
China visit and the delegation he is leading has been deeply
impressed by China's development. He voiced the belief that Poland
and China could further increase their cooperation in every field,
especially in the economic and trade areas.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China attaches importance to its economic and
trade links with Poland, adding the two sides have reached a
consensus on resolving the existing problems in Sino-Polish trade
following their exchange of views on reinforcing bilateral
economic ties since May last year. Sino-Polish economic and trade
cooperation is growing continuously and there are still a lot of
potentials to be tapped in this respect, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said that the Chinese side agrees in principle
to increase imports from Poland by using the export credit
provided by Poland, and China would send a business delegation to
visit Poland very soon to negotiate with the Polish side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
