<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Condemns Attack on Tourists in Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel today condemned the attack on tourists by suspected Islamic
extremists in the Egyptian city of Luxor, in which 66 people were
killed, including 57 foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
"I condemn this repulsive attack by misguided fanatics in the
strongest terms," said Kinkel in a statement, adding that the
attackers were cowards.
</P>
<P>
"Terror must never be allowed as a means for political
confrontation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
His statement said that five diplomats from the German Embassy
in Cairo had arrived in Luxor to identify victims.
</P>
<P>
The tourists killed in the shootout were said to be Japanese,
German and Swiss nationals. Three Egyptians and six of seven
suspected Moslem militants were also killed in the incident, while
24 other foreign tourists were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place at 9:15 a.m. local time at Queen
Hatshepsut's temple near the Valley of the Kings in Luxor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on Farming Policies Opens in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A workshop was held here
today with the theme of "adopting food and agricultural policies
to the changing international environment".
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day workshop, Ethiopian Vice-Minister of
Economic Development and Cooperation Mulatu Teshome said the
Uruguay round of multi-lateral trade negotiations was
successfully concluded in 1994 and their implementation herald a
new era in international trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguay round aims to achieve greater liberalization of
trade in agriculture by restricting the use of trade-distorting
policies such as direct and indirect subsidies to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguay round can be considered to be consistent with the
objectives and priorities of structural adjustment programs of
developing countries that mainly focus on the promotion and
diversification of exports as well as the improvement of foreign
exchange earnings, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister hoped the workshop to come up with viable
mechanism that will help developing countries to take advantage
of the liberalized international trading environment.
</P>
<P>
Gana Diagne, representative of the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) in Ethiopia, told the workshop that the study
on adopting food and agriculture policies to the changing
international environment involves the assessment of the
requirements of the new international trade regime.
</P>
<P>
It also involves the review of the compatibility of domestic
production and trade policies of Ethiopia with these requirements
and the impact of the new international trade relations on the
export earnings of developing countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, jointly organized by the FAO and the Ethiopian
Ministry of Economic Development and Cooperation, is attended by
representatives from Ethiopian ministries, institutions and the
private sector as well as international organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
