<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 60 Killed, 24 Injured in Terror Attack in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 60 people were
confirmed dead and 24 injured in Egypt's largest single terrorist
shooting rampage in the Upper Egyptian city of Luxor this morning,
the Interior Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry issued its first words nearly nine hours after six
unidentified gunmen opened fire randomly at groups of tourists in
front of a desert tourist site and fought a two-hour gun battle
with the police near the Valley of Queens in Luxor, about 560
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-seven Swiss, German and Japanese tourists, two Egyptian
security guards and a tourist guide were among the dead.
</P>
<P>
The injured include 12 Swiss, two Germans, one French and one
Japanese as well as eight Egyptians, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The 11 critically-ill have been flown by helicopters to Cairo
for treatment while those with lesser injuries remain in the Luxor
Hospital. Four lightly injured foreign tourists have been released
after treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Luxor security authority is working with the Tourism
Ministry to identify the ill-fated tourists. Another official
statement by the Interior Ministry in this regard is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that all six gunmen that launched the
shooting spree at around 8:45 a.m. local time were killed in the
shoot-out with the police.
</P>
<P>
But MENA quoted "a top level security source" in Luxor as
saying that there may be a seventh terrorist still at large.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the terrorists fired indiscriminately at the
groups of foreign tourists converging in front of a desert tomb on
the west bank of the Nile before one of them was killed in the
ensuing cross-fire with the security police.
</P>
<P>
The rest fled and were killed in the subsequent exchange of
fire with the police in front of the Hatshepsut Temple in the
Valley of Queens which houses hundreds of Pharaonic tombs.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no claim of responsibility for the attack. But
speculations have it that the Islamic militants scheming to
install pure and stricter Islamic rule in Egypt with violence.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,300 have been killed since 1992 when the Islamic
extremists launched a violent campaign to topple the secular
government led by President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
As the government's crackdown confined the violence to such
southern hideouts as Assuit and Minya further in the south, Luxor
has mainly been free from such attacks until today. Undeterred
foreign tourists kept flocking into Luxor, a top Egyptian tourist
attraction that boasts mammoth Pharaonic temples and royal tombs.
</P>
<P>
This was the second fetal attack in two months targeting
foreign tourists. Nine Germans and their Egyptian driver were
killed on September 18 in a gunshoot and petrol-bomb attack on a
tour bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities Museum in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The two brother carrying out the attack have been sentenced to
death on October 30.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a vulnerable target of terror attacks. However, it
attracted about 4 million tourists and about 3 billion
U.S. dollars to Egypt last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
