<HEADLINE> Windsor Castle Restoration Completed Ahead of Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Restoration work on the
fire-damaged Windsor Castle was completed today after five years
of hard work by 1,500 workers and experts.
</P>
<P>
900-year-old Windsor Castle, the Queen's weekend residence in
southwestern suburb of London, was destroyed by fire on November
20, 1992. More than 100 rooms, covering an area of 7,000 square
meters, were damaged in the blaze, which is thought to have been
started by a spotlight shining on a curtain.
</P>
<P>
At a party she gave for the workers involved in the restoration
project, the Queen Elizabeth said today the completed restoration,
which cost 36.5 million pounds (62 million U.S. dollars), was a
"wonderful anniversary present" to her 50-year marriage scheduled
for later this week.
</P>
<P>
The work was originally expected to be completed by Spring 1998
and the job, with painstaking efforts of the workers, had been
finished six months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Initial estimates put the castle's damage at about 40 million
pounds (68 million dollars), which sparked a public debate about
who should pay for the repairs, as the castle is owned by the
government. Later the Queen agreed to meet 70 percent of the cost
of the restoration work and the government pay the rest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
