<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S Goods, Service Quality Show Overall Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- An annual survey indicated
that the U.S. customers are showing growing dissatisfaction with
goods and services they get in the country over the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
The new data from the American Customer Satisfaction Index
(ACSI) help explain why consumers don't feel better off even
though the nation's economy is strong, according to University of
Michigan Business School economist Claes Fornell.
</P>
<P>
Although the latest data show the Index to be stabilizing, the
ACSI is at its second-lowest level since measuring customer
satisfaction on a national scale begun three years ago. The Index
now stands at 71.1 on a 100-point scale, down nearly 5 percent
since November 1994 when customer satisfaction was at 74.5.
</P>
<P>
The products with most significant decline in satisfaction
rating include athletic clothing and running shoes, soft drinks
and food processing. The customers are most dissatisfied with the
service in transportation and communication utilities, with the
rating down by 5.2 percent
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing and nondurables rating is based on interviews
with 13,375 customers of 43 companies in 10 major industries.
</P>
<P>
The University of Michigan Business School is the home of the
National Quality Research Center (NQRC) where the Index is
compiled..  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
