<HEADLINE> China Places Priority on Automobile Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
in charge of China's automotive industry says that China places
high priority on the introduction and development of automotive
safety.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government is extending great efforts to
reduce traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoyu, director of the Automotive Department under the
Ministry of Machinery(MOM), made the remarks at today's Automotive
Safety Technology Seminar jointly sponsored by Sweden-based Volvo
and the China Machinery Consultants International.
</P>
<P>
The safety issue has prevailed since the introduction of
China's automotive industry some 110 years ago, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Domestic automobile manufacturers have lagged behind in
introducing safety technology, said Zhang, adding that China
nonetheless introduced 25 compulsory rules governing operations of
the industry.
</P>
<P>
China has also established three test centers to ensure the
safety of domestically-produced vehicles, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The director called for expanded international cooperation in
the sector in order to help China's automotive industry adopt
international practices at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1992 show that China had 22.8 million motor
vehicles, with the highway death toll standing at 58,700
people. The number of related injuries stood at 114,000 people,
with economic losses for the year ending at 640 million
yuan. Respective figures for 1996 jumped to 28.8 million, 73,700,
174,000, and 1.72 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending the seminar joined in in-depth discussions on
the development of automobile safety. Bjorn Lundell, a senior
design Engineer for Volvo, briefed participants on the Swedish
company's experience in the field.
</P>
<P>
Lars-Ake Skager, deputy mayor of Gothenburg, Germany, the Volvo
headquarters, briefed participants on cooperation between the city
government and the company.
</P>
<P>
Volvo, one of the world's major automobile manufacturers,
entered the Chinese market in 1976, with the company's Beijing
Office established in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Leif Engstrom, the company's chief representative in Beijing,
noted that over 6,000 Volvos are currently in operation in
China. He noted that Volvo has opened 18 maintenance centers and
sales outlets across the country.
</P>
<P>
Engstrom pointed to the fact that China's automotive industry
is still relatively underdeveloped, and noted that the country
offers great opportunities for international motor vehicle
manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Strives to Stamp out Maritime Transport Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
launched a campaign aimed at stamping out maritime transport
accidents and upgrading quality shipping in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Maritime accidents claim an average 1,000 lives and 230 vessels
a year worldwide, according to a senior official on the
commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
"On average, 230 vessels with a gross registered tonnage of 1.1
million are lost worldwide every year, claiming more than 1,000
lives and often causing irreparable environmental damage," said
Commissioner in Transport Neil Kinnock.
</P>
<P>
Though the large majority of maritime operators in Europe and
elsewhere in the world fulfil and often exceed the best standards
of safety and seaworthiness, said the commissioner, there are
still too many owners and users of shipping who put the pursuit of
short-term profit far above any considerations of safety and
civilized conditions.
</P>
<P>
"The result," Kinnock said, "are seen in unfair competition, in
preventable danger, in appalling living and working conditions on
board ships and too often in tragedy."
</P>
<P>
The European Commission pledged to continue to work closely
with such international organizations as the International
Maritime Organization to ensure the proper implementation of
international rules for both the merchant shipping fleet and for
passenger vessels of all flags when trading in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The commission has proposed that from July 1 next year any
vessel entering EU ports should be certified under the
International Safety Management code and that ships without such
certification will be detained until they have a valid
certification.
</P>
<P>
"We are not seeking to multiply regulations for their own sake.
The priority will be given to binding quality standards for flag
administrations and registers rather than composing further new
demands that would widen the cost gap for honest and responsible
operators," the commissioner added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0044 </DOCNO>
