<HEADLINE> Vaccine Campaign Unveiled in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A large vaccine campaign
started on Sunday in the northeast and northwestern regions of
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF),
World Health Organization (WHO) and the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) are involved in the vaccination in an
effort to immunize 400,000 Somali children under five from polio,
one of the six killer diseases.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Bosasso said 350 local doctors and nurses are
carrying out the work in the regions of Bosasso, Nugal and Mudug
on four-wheel drive vehicles, camel caravans and donkey carts to
the remote areas where transportation has been affected by the
rains.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of the breakaway Republic of Somaliland, the
vaccine campaign was inaugurated in the presidential palace of
Mohamed Hagi Ibrahim Egal.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 people are reported to be working for the
campaign in Somaliland. According to the WHO officials in
Hargeisa, the capital city, about six million African children
were vaccinated last year, while this year they plan to immunize
eight million children from polio.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will continue for four days in the main towns as
well as the remote villages provided the security situation
permits.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is part of a worldwide polio vaccination
operation meant to eradicate the disease from the earth surface
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. agencies, the immunization campaign will
be confined to the northeast and northwest regions because the
southern regions of the country are inaccessible due to serious
floods which has lasted about a month now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
