<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provincial Security Chief Killed by Traffickers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Security commander of Iran's
southeastern province of Sistan and Baluchestan, Brigadier General
Javad Hajj Khodakaram, has been killed by drug traffickers, local
evening newspaper "Kayhan" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Khodakaram was shot dead in an ambush
plotted by drug traffickers at 18:00 local time Saturday evening
when he was inspecting the country's borders with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The group of smugglers fled from the site under the cover of
twilight after the killing, the daily added, without mentioning
whether there were other casualties.
</P>
<P>
Due to its adjacency to the drug-producing center of the
"Golden Crescent" bordering Afghanistan, Pakistan and Iran, Sistan
and Baluchestan province is a frontier of Iran's combat against
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The country's northeast province of Khorasan is the other
important transit for drug smugglers from the "Golden Crescent".
</P>
<P>
A newspaper report on Saturday said that over 4,000 kilograms
of opium were seized in Khorasan province in two separate armed
encounters with the smugglers during three days.
</P>
<P>
Iran passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989, which empowered
the authorities to issue the death penalty to any drug trafficker
caught with more than 30 grams of heroin or 5,000 grams of opium.
</P>
<P>
The country intensified its campaign by allowing the imposition
of hard labor punishment on drug traffickers and addicts.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking is a major social problem in the country that
one of the main transit routes for drugs destined for Europe
coming from the "Golden Crescent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
