<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today criticized the
U.S. Congress for adding certain conditions to an economic
assistance program for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press conference here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that such a action
is "an interference in Turkey's domestic affairs."
</P>
<P>
The House demanded recently that half of the 40 million
U.S. dollar economic assistance to Ankara should be distributed
to some democratic groups, according to Atacanli.
</P>
<P>
Such a decision was made as the House discussed the assistance
program presented by the U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
"This move is in contradiction with the spirit of the
agreements signed by the two countries, " Atacanli said,
describing it as "totally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also said that the Turkish government is
disappointed in the U.S. Congress's decision to reduce the
economic assistance from 50 million dollars to 40 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
This reduction was caused by the pressure of some
anti-Turkish lobbies on the Capital Hill, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli said that the Turkish ambassador in Washington had
informed the U.S administration Turkey's dissatisfaction with the
change of the assistance program. 
</P>
