<HEADLINE> French Insecticide Enters U.S. Corn Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The French chemical and
pharmaceutical corporation Rhone-Poulenc is selling its new
insecticide Regent to the United States corn market, after the
chemical product was recently approved by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
The approval of Regent marks the first introduction in the U.S.
of the insecticidal active ingredient for agricultural use, and
will allow Rhone Poulenc to increase its sale of insecticidal
products to 250 million U.S. dollars in 1998, said Rhone-Poulenc
Agro, a branch of the corporation in a news release today.
</P>
<P>
Regent, which will be available to U.S. corn growers from 1998,
will be the only corn soil insecticide that controls two key
insects simultaneously at planting application, said the company.
</P>
<P>
The insecticide protects against corn root worm and European corn
borer which consistently rank as two most economically damaging
corn pests in the United States, said the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
