<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Supports Bi-Communal Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government is in
favor of meetings between Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
businessmen in a bid for short and long-term cooperation, a
government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said "in the past we neglected the
importance of economic cooperation between the two
communities. That was a mistake."
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the results of a seminar held in Brussels
last week, which was attended by businessmen from the two
communities from Cyprus, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, entitled "In Economic Cooperation Lies Mutual
Benefit", was organized by the Columbia University, New York, and
the Peace Research Institute in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
Similar meetings were also held in Istanbul, Turkey and Athens,
Greece in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
"There are problems and difficulties but they can be overcome
through sincere cooperation," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed, however, that activities should in no
way contain elements that might lead to direct or indirect
recognition of the breakaway entity unilaterally established in
the Turkish-occupied northern part of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the government would support the implementation
of measures agreed upon by the business people in Brussels,
Christofides said the Cypriot government would wait for full
details before expressing its position.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops took over the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed Greek Cypriot
coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "the Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was only recognized by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
