<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Calls Arabs Boycotting MENA Gathering Losers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Displeaed with the Arab boycott
of the on-going Doha regional economic conference, a senior
U.S. official today called the rejectionists "losers" in the
cooperation process this gathering is meant to promote.
</P>
<P>
"Those who chose to come are the winners," said Stuart
Eizenstat, U.S. under-secretary for economic, business and
agricultural affairs, while commenting on the boycott adopted by a
dozen Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Those Arab countries, including Egypt and Saudi Arabia,
preferred to stay away from the three-day Arab-Israeli Middle East
and North Africa conference which opened here Sunday. They cited
the lack of progress on the peace track as reasons for their
absence.
</P>
<P>
This turned out to be a major embarassment for the U.S., which,
as a patron of Israel, has vehemently supported the holding of the
conference and tried its best to persuade those Arabs into
participating, even at a lower level.
</P>
<P>
The conference did scale down from an originally anticipated
summit to the one now represented only by ministers. However, the
Arabs argued their philosophy that no Arab-Israeli economic
cooperation should take place without progress in peace.
</P>
<P>
"Those who didn't come are sending a signal that the Middle
East is potentially going to slide back into the same motion of
putting politics first," Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
He nonetheless expressed satisfaction over the turnout at the
conference - an estimated 2,000 attendants from more than 60
countries, including 850 business representatives.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the region wants politics to come second after
the need for economic development, he paraphrased.
</P>
<P>
Expounding U.S. wisdom on the relationship between economic
cooperation and peace process, Eizenstat said that during a tough
period of the peace process, the economic dimension could "help
indicate what can happen in a positive way," and "the peace
process will accelerate."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, we (U.S.) are not naive and know that the
political situation of the peace process is an important
ingredient," he said, adding economic cooperation and economic
dimension reinforce each other.
</P>
<P>
"Under the very difficult circumstances of the peace process,
this (the conference) is an enormous success," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
