<HEADLINE> UK Public Become Less Hostile to EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 17 (Xinhua) - British voters are less hostile
to the economic and monetary union (EMU) since Chancellor Gordon
Brown committed the UK to the principle of joining, according to a
new poll.
</P>
<P>
Brown told Commons on 26 October that "If a single currency
would be good for British jobs, business and future prosperity, it
is right, in principle, to join."
</P>
<P>
However, if a referendum was called today, the public would
still vote against participation with "No" votes outnumber "Yes"
by a margin of 22 percent, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
But this compares with 27 percent before the Chancellor's commons
statement on 26 October. It is the lowest figure for three years,
the research conducted by the US investment bank Salomaon Brothers
shows.
</P>
<P>
The Mori poll also suggested that the Government's stance could
affect the outcome of a referendum.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the Government were to urge strongly that Britain
should be part of EMU, the gap between the "Yes" and "No" votes
falls to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
"An outcome along these lines would still leave the Government
facing defeat, but the full weight of the Government's powers of
persuasion has yet to be felt," said Michael Saunders, the Bank's
economist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
