<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Shows Future of Travel at World Travel Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 17 (Xinhua) - IBM, the world's largest
computer company, today delivered its vision of the future of
travel at London's World Travel Market 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the future, people will be selecting, booking and paying for
their travel via the internet, viewing hotel rooms and holiday
resorts via their home computers, and conducting business trip
expenses on "Smart Cards" which act as electronic purses.
</P>
<P>
People will pass through immigration by placing their hand on
an electronic reader that instantly cross-references their hand
geometry with millions of records, according to IBM.
</P>
<P>
People will always be assured of their favorite room, meal,
and seat through stored data that means carriers will be able to
pamper them as never before, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
The journey of the future, as outlined by IBM, will reduce the
need for queuing to check in at airports and hotels, and will see
travelers booking hire cars, restaurants and theater tickets from
wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, Claude Guay, Director Travel
Distribution Solutions, said: "The future is here already. Over 50
percent of the financial transactions conducted on the Internet in
1997 involved travel, and this is set to explode in the near
future."
</P>
<P>
"We have created ways of booking, reserving, and paying
securely for flights on the Internet already, and switched-on
business travelers are already taking advantage." he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
