<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Defends Decision Not to Attend Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said today that his decision of not attending the Doha
economic conference was a result of consultations with Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and related American representatives.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that before making the decision he had talks with
Netanyahu and U.S. officials for their opinion.
</P>
<P>
After the consultation, he said, he conceived that the main
focus of the meeting was economic, not political and it would be
preferable that a senior economic minister should head the Israeli
delegation to Doha.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky is leading
a 100-member delegation, including government officials,
businessmen and journalists, to the Middle East and North Africa
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor Knesset (Parliament) member Uzi Beilin has
criticized that Levy made a terrible mistake by staying away from
the Doha conference, noting that would give Arab States reasons to
divert the conference away from the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in contrast to previous conference, the U.S. today
did not object to the release of a statement against Israel by the
meeting. Observers in Qatar attributed this to Levy's staying
away, because U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had
pressed Israel to send Levy to the conference.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the conference called on Israel to honor
signed agreements and United Nations Security Council Resolutions
242 and 338, and noted that any Middle East peace accord must
based on the land for peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The Doha conference, which opened Sunday and will conclude
Tuesday, is being boycotted by a majority of the 22 members of the
Arab League. These nations have accused Israel of refusing to
trade land for peace with the Palestinians and responsible for the
current peace crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
