<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Sets Preconditions for Turkish Cypriots' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government set
preconditions of Turkish Cypriots' participation in negotiations
on Cyprus' accession to the European Union (EU), due to begin
early next year.
</P>
<P>
At his daily press briefing here today, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said that the preconditions for Turkish
Cypriot participation is that participants support accession and
the Turkish occupation regime receives no recognition.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on press reports citing British special envoy
for Cyprus Sir David Hannay as saying that the question is whether
a way can be found for the representation of Turkish Cypriot
so-called governmental organizations in the accession talks.
</P>
<P>
"If the Cyprus problem is resolved, then the two federal states
will be officially represented," the Spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
"For as long as the Cyprus problem remains unresolved and
since the U.N. (resolution 541) asks that no other state but the
Republic of Cyprus is recognized as the legal government, we
can not but insist on our preconditions," Christofides added.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has proposed the participation of
Turkish Cypriot organizations, such as political parties and trade
unions, in the official delegation of the Republic of Cyprus for
EU talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU full membership in 1990. The EU has
confirmed its decision in March 1995 that the accession talks
with Cyprus will begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
But the EU's decision was rejected by Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash, who refused to further negotiations for a Cyprus
settlement unless the EU freezes plans for accession talks with
the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops took over the northern
third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
