<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal Calls for End to Angolan Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Jose Lamego, Portugal's
secretary of state for foreign affairs and cooperation, today
called on all parties involved to put an immediate end to the
peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to Angolan newsmen in Lisbon after a
meeting with Paulo Cassoma, governor of Huambo province in Angola
who is on a visit to Portugal, the Angolan News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It's been nearly three years since the Lusaka Peace Accord was
signed on November 20, 1994, but peace is still out of sight, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace pact calls for a government of national
reconciliation and a single national army in Angola, ending
nearly two decades of civil war in the country since the two
warring sides inked the accord in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, articles of the accord have not been stuck to by the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), and
for this sanctions were imposed on the former rebel movement
UNITA on October 30 by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
As an observer to the peace process, Lamego noted, Portugal
urged that national authority be re-established in all parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Portugal wishes to strengthen and consolidate its ties with
Angola, Lamego said, adding his country will work together with
the United States and Russia to promote the development in the
peace process and bring peace to the worn-torn country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Criticizes UN Policy Over Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister
Fares Boueiz today criticized the United Nations for exerting
different standards on Iraq and Israel over the implementation of
relevant resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"The treatment to Iraq is too severe," Boueiz said in an
interview with Iranian Islamic TV today.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. is taking a severe position over Iraq issue
while disregarding the implementation of those resolutions related
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq is being punished due to the reported possession of
weapons of mass destruction, but it is only a presumption," he
said, "Israel is outside the punishment although it refuses to
observe the U.N. resolutions and to sign to the treaty on nuclear
weapons control."
</P>
<P>
Iraq is faced with a military attack by the U.S. after it
expelled American personnel working with the U.N. arms inspection
teams on charges of carrying out spying activities.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, U.N. Security Council met and issued a resolution
strongly condemning Iraq's expulsion of the U.S. weapon inspectors
and demanding it rescind its decision immediately.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz criticized the U.N. for not imposing any sanctions on
countries defying its resolutions except Iraq, saying that it
appears there are different levels and standards based on
different countries and interests.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.N. to take the same standard to treat every
single country equally.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in south
Lebanon to prevent cross-border Lebanese guerrilla attacks. Israel
refuses to observe the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425
demanding Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
