<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders to Attend Trade, Investment Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state from five
of the 14 Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries
are expected to attend a two-day trade and investment summit in
Gaborone, Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The Herald Tribune-Southern African trade and investment
summit, which is to be held on Tuesday and Wednesday, will
discuss the future of the SADC region, South African Press
Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be addressed by Botswana President Ketumile
Masire, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Mozambican President
Joaquim Chissano and Namibian Prime Minister Hagen Geingob.
</P>
<P>
South African Gauteng Premier Tokyo Sexwale will also make a
speech.
</P>
<P>
The summit will look at opportunities for long-term investment
in southern Africa, the outlook for increasing intra-regional
trade, south-south investment, the development of regional
infrastructure and privatization.
</P>
<P>
It will also look at opportunities on southern Africa's stock
markets. Chilean Finance Minister Eduardo Aninat and the economic
adviser to the Malaysian government, Tun Daim Zainuddin, will
speak at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Namibia will hold a similar conference next year. 
</P>
