<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa to Import More Oil from Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today said in Saudi Arabia that his country would
increase oil import from the world's top oil producer and exporter
by 15,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the announcement before wrapping up his two-day
visit to the kingdom. He told a press conference that a Memorandum
of Understanding to this effect has been signed.
</P>
<P>
According to reports by Kuwait News Agency from Saudi capital
Riyadh, Mandela said the Saudi Aramco Company, its only
state-owned oil producing and exporting conglomerate, would follow
up the details of this project, along with the construction of an
oil refinery in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is currently one of the major oil suppliers to
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The memo was a result of Mandela's first official visit to the
Gulf Kingdom since assuming power in 1994 ending the apartheid
regime in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by a high-ranking delegation that included the
ministers of defense, metals and energy, and public utilities,
Mandela arrived in Riyadh Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with Saudi King Fahd and Crown Prince Abdallah
Bin Abdel Aziz on means of boosting bilateral relations and the
stalled Middle East peace process, and on the current stand-off
between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the ministers met their Saudi counterparts for
talks on boosting cooperation in the fields of defense, minerals,
oil and trade.
</P>
<P>
On the current Iraq-U.N. crisis, Mandela called for a peaceful
settlement through diplomatic means, adding that his country
"supports all efforts aimed at peacefully solving the crisis away
from the use of force."
</P>
<P>
He also called on Iraq to "fully implement all U.N. resolutions
so that the plight of the Iraqi people ends."
</P>
<P>
Mandela's visit to Saudi Arabia came two months after a visit
to South Africa by Saudi second Deputy Premier and Minister of
Defense Prince Sultan Bin Abdel Aziz in September.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and South Africa established diplomatic relations
in 1994 after Mandela took office. Since then, official
exchanges between the two countries have been on the increase.
</P>
<P>
In addition, trade exchange between the two countries jumped
from 42.7 million U.S. dollars in 1994 to 433.6 million in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Army Exercises Protested in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot environmentalists
gathered from Sunday in the Akamas peninsula, at the western tip
of the island, to protest against British Forces' military
exercises in the area.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued today by the British Forces said
90 Episkopi-based soldiers would have low level training in
Akamas region between November 17 and 21, using hand-held
infantry-type weapons and, at times, live ammunitions.
</P>
<P>
"Such weapons present almost no hazard to the environment,"
the press release said, adding that stringent regulations will be
enforced to preserve and protect the landscape.
</P>
<P>
Akamas is one of the few regions in the Mediterranean where the
green and loggerhead turtles hatch their eggs. Local
environmentalists have called for the establishment of a national
park in Akamas peninsula.
</P>
<P>
A group of environmentalists, gathered since Sunday, tried
twice to stop the 20 military vehicles carrying British soldiers
to Akamas.
</P>
<P>
They were prevented by the Cypriot police but finally managed
to hand the officer in charge a petition calling for an immediate
end to these exercises.
</P>
<P>
Britain has retained two sovereign bases in Cyprus since
1960, when it granted the island its independence from colonial
rule.
</P>
<P>
British Forces in Cyprus could conduct annual military
exercises for about 70 days in accordance with the 1960 Treaty
of Establishment of the Cyprus Republic.
</P>
<P>
"Discussion continues between the Republic of Cyprus'
government and British authorities regarding the possibility of
an alternate training area to replace the Akamas," the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Cyprus' House of Representatives approved
unanimously a resolution, calling for an end to British forces
exercises in Akamas.
</P>
<P>
It called on the government of the Republic to stop giving its
approval to exercises in this region and to "take all necessary
measures".
</P>
<P>
The resolution described Britain's right to use the area for
military purposes as a colonial legacy.
</P>
<P>
It authorized House President Spyros Kyprianou to make a
recourse on the issue to the European Parliament, the
Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe, the Commonwealth
Parliamentary Association and the House of Commons of Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0078 </DOCNO>
