<HEADLINE> Annan Is Encouraged by Iraqi Latest Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said here today he was encouraged by Iraqi government's
latest moves.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief was responding to Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz's remark in Paris that Iraq would readmit American arms
inspectors if the United Nations agreed to change the makeup of
the inspection teams with equal representation given to each
Permanent Member of the Security Council of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Annan said all sorts of efforts were
being made to try to find a diplomatic solution to the present
crisis and Aziz's remark was part of that effort.
</P>
<P>
Annan said this was at least a movement from Iraqi original
position where it was adamant that there should be no Americans.
</P>
<P>
Annan said it was encouraging and everybody was trying to
avoid a conflict and resolve the crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis over the arms inspection began on October
29 when Iraq vowed to expel Americans weapons inspectors working
for the United Nations and to shoot down American U-2 planes.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors are part of the teams monitoring Iraqi
compliance with the United Nations resolutions demanding that
it destroy all its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
