<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Syria Hope to Avert Iraqi-US Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The visiting first deputy
Premier and Foreign Minister of Kuwait Sheikh Ahmed Al Sabah and
his Syrian counterpart Farouq Sharaa today expressed hope for
averting any military confrontation between Iraq and the US.
</P>
<P>
In a departure statement in Damascus, upon the conclusion of
his two-day visit to Syria, Sheikh Sabah said "we hope that no
military confrontation will take place in the region, and should
such confrontation occur it will not be our doing."
</P>
<P>
He called upon Iraq to implement the UN Security Council
resolutions, particularly the latest ones.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Sharaa, who was seeing off Sheikh Sabah, said on
the same issue that "we hope that no escalation takes place
because confrontation is not in the interest of any party, nor is
it in the interest of security and stability in the region. But,
at the same time we have always been for commitment to the related
U.N. Security Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Sharaa denied any current Syrian-Egyptian efforts to deal with
the crisis or the tense situation between the Security Council and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa revealed a prospective visit to Syria by Iraqi deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz within his current tour. He said, "Aziz
may visit Damascus in the course of his present tour, and it is him
who has requested that.
</P>
<P>
Should the visit take place, discussions will take into account
the interests of Kuwait, the Iraqi people and the Gulf region as
well as the Arab situation as a whole, he said, adding that Syria
is of the view that any crisis affecting any part of the Arab
homeland ought to be treated in a manner that serves the supreme
Arab interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
