<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 65 Militants Stand Trial in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Supreme Military
Court today opened trial of leaders of Gamaa Islamia (Islamic
Group), as Islamic militants carried out a deadly attack on
foreign tourists in south of the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 65 defendants were indicted for joining the illegal
group that was established with the aim of overthrowing the
government.
</P>
<P>
They also were accused of monitoring the movement of public
personalities with the aim of killing them, and planned to attack
public places for the purpose of stealing.
</P>
<P>
They stocked firearms and other weapons, forged documents and
possessed unlicensed ammunition, the presiding judge read the
indictment before adjourning the hearings to December 3 to give a
chance to counsels to prepare their defense.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group has been leading a violent campaign to
overthrow the Egyptian secular government. Nearly 1,300 have been
killed since 1992, most of them policemen and militants.
</P>
<P>
The group is widely suspected of being responsible for Egypt's
largest single terrorist attack which hit the archeological resort
of Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo, this morning.
</P>
<P>
At least 60 people were confirmed dead and 24 injured after six
unidentified gunmen opened fire randomly at groups of tourists in
front of a desert tourist site and fought a two-hour gun battle
with the police near the Valley of Queens.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-seven Swiss, German and Japanese tourists, two Egyptian
security guards and a tourist guide were among the dead.
</P>
<P>
The wounded were 12 Swiss, two Germans, one French and one
Japanese as well as eight Egyptian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The attack which targeted the highly vulnerable and profitable
tourist industry is apparently a retaliation for the government
crackdown on militants that involved massive arrests, military
trials and executions.
</P>
<P>
Less than two months ago, nine German tourists and their
Egyptian drive were killed in a shoot-out and firebomb attack on a
bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities Museum in Cairo. The two
assailants have been sentenced to death on October 30.
</P>
<P>
Tourism brought about some 3 billion U.S. dollars in revenue to
Egypt last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU Ministerial Meeting Opens in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Western European
Union (WEU) opened their two-day ministerial meetings today in the
eastern German city of Erfurt to discuss how to re-define the role
of the western European defense group in the post-Cold-War era.
</P>
<P>
Present at The meetings were foreign and defense ministers from
28 European states, including 10 WEU full member states and 10
central and eastern European states which are WEU's associated
partners.
</P>
<P>
During the first-day discussions which were conducted within
the armaments group of the WEU, ministers agreed to set up a joint
agency to coordinate European armaments development and
production.
</P>
<P>
According to German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, the agency
is expected to help cut European armaments costs, facilitate joint
operations of European armed forces and to strengthen Europe's
competitiveness against U.S. armaments industry.
</P>
<P>
A concrete plan for the establishment of the agency would be
worked out in the next 12 months, Ruehe said.
</P>
<P>
The primary discussions of the WEU meetings will come on
Tuesday with main topics including the institutional linkage
between the WEU and the European Union (EU), military cooperation
between the WEU and the NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization)
as well as integration of central and eastern European states into
the WEU.
</P>
<P>
The 10 full members of the WEU are Belgium, Britain, France,
Germany, Greece,, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and
Spain. Moreover, it also has three associated members: Iceland,
Norway and Turkey, as well as five states which now have observer
status: Austria, Denmark, Finland, Ireland, Sweden.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Iraq's Latest Compromise Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Monday rejected an offer for compromise from Iraq to end the
confrontation between Washington and Baghdad by giving the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council the equal
authority in the U.N. weapons inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
"It's not up to iraq to determine the composition of U.N.
inspection teams," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
"It's up to the U.N. to determine that, so whatever feelings
Iraq has are immaterial."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said in an interview
with Le Figaro in Paris on Sunday that Iraq would re-admit
American weapons inspectors back if the United Nations agreed to
change the makeup of the inspection teams with equal
representation given to each permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The permanent members of the U.N. Security Council include
Britain, China, France, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We asked the Security Council to create a committee of experts
whose impartiality is not in question," Aziz told the French
newspaper Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
"it would be necessary that in this new team of inspectors,
the five permanent members would all have the same weight," he
added.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Iraq presented the proposal at the United
Nations about a week ago but there was "not much enthusiasm for
it."
</P>
<P>
"We're continuing to stress in our diplomatic contacts the
importance of a clear message to Baghdad that they should back
down and allow the inspections to occur," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
