<HEADLINE> Clinton Promotes Welfare Hiring Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday visited the Cessna Aircraft Co. in Wichita, Kansas, to
promote companies' special efforts to find jobs for welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and several Cabinet members headed to the dedication of
a new job training facility at Cessna, which already had won
national recognition for helping to move welfare recipients into
the workplace, United Press International reported.
</P>
<P>
The event is part of Clinton's efforts with the Welfare to Work
Partnership, a nationwide non-partisan group of private businesses
pledged to promote efforts to train and employ workers from among
welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to announce that 2,500 companies have
joined the partnership in its first six months, far exceeding his
goal of 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The president will also announce new financial penalties,
reaching 5 percent of federal welfare funds, for states that do
not meet federally mandated goals for employing welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
Under a 7-year-old program at Cessna, the worldwide leader in
the production of single-engine aircraft, small groups of
unemployed or low- skilled workers are taught blueprint reading,
shop math and basic sheet metal assembly skills.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, Cessna has hired 262 people for its sheet metal
assembly training program.
</P>
<P>
The new Cessna facility will allow the 70-year-old company to
double its welfare-to-work program and provide on-site child care
for trainees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
