<HEADLINE> Anti-War Groups to Protest U.S. Military Action on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Some anti-war groups based
in Washington D.C. will stage a protest against the latest round
of U.S. military threatening to Iraq, the National People's
Campaign (NPC), one of the anti-war groups said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The protest, which will take the form of a picket line and a
rally in front of the White House on Tuesday, is part of an
international campaign of protests this week, including 9 U.S.
cities, the NPC said.
</P>
<P>
The NPC also called for an end to the sanctions imposed upon
Iraq since 1991.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions have killed an estimated 1.4 million Iraqis,
including over half a million children," the NPC quoted the
International Action Center as saying, which had a delegation
just returned from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
A poll, released on Sunday by Newsweek, found Americans are
divided over whether the United States should take military
action against Iraq as a way to force Baghdad to back down on
expulsion of American inspectors.
</P>
<P>
About half, or 49 percent, of those polled say Iraq's
decision to ban Americans from United Nations inspection teams
warrants military action. But nearly as many, or 41 percent,
oppose military action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
