<HEADLINE> Kuwait Opposes Military Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Kuwaiti Foreign
Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahamd Al-Jaber said here today that
Kuwait opposes any military attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark upon arrival at the Beirut International
Airport tonight on a three-day visit to Lebanon after a trip to
Egypt and Syria.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with his Lebanese counterpart Farez Boueiz,
Al-Jaber said he is not sure if military attacks will be launched
on Iraq, adding it depends on the stance of Iraq and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that only solution to the crisis is Iraq's
implementation of the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Last week Iraq expelled six Americans working with the U.N.
Special Commission monitoring Baghdad's weapons destruction, on
charges of espionage. It now faces U.S. threat of military action
in the standoff.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al-Jaber explained to Boueiz the reason Kuwait
attends the ongoing Doha economic conference, saying the
participation is not meant to being against Lebanon and Syria,
both of which boycotted the gathering because it also includes
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait sent only a low level official to the conference, he
said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Al-Jaber will meet Lebanon's leadership and
for discussions on the regional situation. 
</P>
