<HEADLINE> SKorean Currency Drops to 1,012.80 against U.S. dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korean currency and stock
markets continued its tumble Tuesday, with the won hitting its
daily allowable low of 1,012.80 to one dollar in early trade.
</P>
<P>
The won's plunge came only moments after the market started its
morning session, dealers said. The average rate stood at 990.60
won, compared with Monday's close at 1,008.60 won.
</P>
<P>
The central bank did not intervene during the day. It withdrew
from the market Monday after supporting the local currency for
several days.
</P>
<P>
Excessive speculation, growing jitters over domestic financial
markets and high demand for import payments have combined to weigh
on the won, said a dealer at a foreign bank branch here.
</P>
<P>
A market participant predicted that the central bank would step
in again when the won hits 1,050 level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices dropped 0.47 percent and then rose
steadly on hopes of a possible loan from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The composite index plunged more than 20 points from the
previous day's closing to 476.30 during the morning session,
nudged by the continuing depreciation of the won.
</P>
<P>
During the afternoon trading, speculation of an imminent
government appeal to the IMF for aid brought the market to 500.49
points at one time.
</P>
<P>
However, the hopes settled down toward the end of the day. The
market closed at 494.66 points, down 2.32 points from the previous
day's closing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
