<HEADLINE> Genscher Calls for EU-China Political Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Predicting that China will become
"an important pillar in the world politics of the 21st century",
former German foreign minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher has called
on Europe to form a political partnership with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Genscher, who just ended a visit to Beijing on November 11-12,
made the appeal in an article titled "Europe and China", which is
due to be published by the Berlin Tagesspiegel newspaper on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent frequent high-level contacts between
China, the United States, Russia and Japan, Genscher said: "The
multi-polar world, which has replaced the bi-polar one of the Cold
War, is taking a more and more clear shape."
</P>
<P>
While Washington, Moscow and Tokyo are taking the common
approach to see China not only as an economic but also a political
partner, people cannot yet talk about a China-policy of the
European Union (EU), Genscher added.
</P>
<P>
"Europe must realize that China will become an important pillar
in the world politics of the 21st century. And this calls for a
political partnership between the EU with China," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the course of the 21st century will depend on
whether a world order based on equality and cooperation will be
established. "Such a world order is unimaginable without the full
participation of China."
</P>
<P>
"The inclusion of China in all developments is indispensable
for global stability. Its quickest possible admission into the
World Trade Organization (WTO) and its future participation in the
world economic summit of the Group 8 are therefore of great
importance," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also stressed that the decision on forming a
Europe-China strategic partnership ought to be made by Europe
itself, not by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"It is now up to Europe to resolutely exploit the opportunities
opened up by the end of the Cold War. Only then can Europe take
its seat in the multi-polar world order of the 21st century,"
Genscher concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
