<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Dips to New Low Despite Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee today
dipped to a new 21-month low at 37.40/42 rupees per U.S. dollar in
a panic-driven market, not heeding to a strong statement by the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) that it would prevent "overshooting"
of the currency.
</P>
<P>
After opening lower at 36.91/94 at the Foreign Exchange Market
in Bombay, the rupee slid to 37.55 per dollar at noon despite RBI
floating 150 million dollars in the market gripped by frenzied
corporate buying and covering by importers, Press Trust of India
said.
</P>
<P>
However, RBI Governor C. Rangarajan's statement that "there is
no ground for a further weakening of the rupee" propped up the
currency to 37.35/39. The RBI's reference rate for the day stood
at 37.52 rupees per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dealers felt that the market will test the 37.50 benchmark at
which the RBI had come out with the statement and said this is
seen as a cap defined by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing the strong economic fundamentals in the
country, Rangarajan said in his statement, "We believe that the
adjustment that has already taken place in the value of the rupee
is adequate."
</P>
<P>
The rupee depreciated by nearly 15 paise (0.15 rupee) Monday
and by over a rupee since November 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
