<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Meets Niger Visitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of
the Central Military Commission, met with Moussa Djermakoye, chief
of general staff of the Armed Forces of Niger, here today.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also state councillor and minister of national defense,
said he was glad to see Sino-Niger bilateral ties had a sound
development since the two nations restored diplomatic relations
last year.
</P>
<P>
He told the visitor the Chinese Government greatly appreciated
the independent foreign policy of peace and nonalignment pursued
by the Niger government under the leadership of President Ibrahim
Mainassara Barre, as well as the government's "one China" stand.
</P>
<P>
"China has much in common with Niger. There are only common
interests, but no conflicts of interests, between the two
countries," Chi said, adding that "Chief Djermakoye would feel
Chinese people's profound friendly sentiments toward the Niger
people during his visit."
</P>
<P>
Chi said he believed Djermakoye's visit would contribute to
promoting the Sino-Niger friendship and cooperative ties, and that
of the two armies would also be upgraded to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Djermakoye said he was deeply impressed by the efforts of the
Chinese people for safeguarding world peace and stability and
maintaining the national respects.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Niger and China, both developing countries, share
identical views on many important issues such as human rights.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the two countries and the two armies would further
strengthen their cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
