<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Presidential Candidates Spurt for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 18 (Xinhua) -- With 30 days away from the
presidential election, South Korea's three key presidential
candidates and their parties are sparing no efforts to raise their
popularity ratings.
</P>
<P>
While Kim Dae-jung from the main opposition National Congress
for New Politics (NCNP) intends to keep his lead, Lee Hoi-chang of
the largest New Korea Party (NKP) and Rhee In-je of the New Party
by the People (NPP) are vying desperately for the second place.
</P>
<P>
Latest polls showed that Kim Dae-jung still tops candidates in
popularity although his support rating has fallen to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fiercest rivalry is expected to be between Rhee and
Lee. The latter's popularity rating has for the first time
overtaken Rhee's according to the latest opinion polls by seven
major dailies.
</P>
<P>
While these two candidates hope to clinch the second place for
a final contest with Kim Dae-jung, Kim himself hopes that a
neck-and-neck competition between Rhee and Lee will enhance his
chance of success.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung is focusing on such large voting blocs as Seoul,
Taegu and North Kyongsang Province (TK region) where the latest
polls showed his popularity is declining.
</P>
<P>
Kim's NCNP and its ally the United Liberal Democrats (ULD) will
start their campaigns throughout the country this week to boost
Kim's popularity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lee Hoi-chang's NKP, desperately trying to turn the
three-way race into a showdown between Lee and Kim, are prepared
to launch various political activities to boost Lee's chance of
winning the election.
</P>
<P>
Rhee In-je, on the other hand, is seeking to generate a
"whirlwind of support" through his campaign tours. His NPP is
planning to bring Park Chan-jong and some other political
heavyweights from the NKP into its fold.
</P>
<P>
While trying to gain the broadest possible support, the parties
have resumed trading accusations to contain each other's support
rates.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP and the NPP are renewing attacks on the NKP's Lee with
the past controversy surrounding his two sons. The NKP countered
by saying that the 73-year-old Kim is too old to be a president
and Rhee broke his promise to split the NKP after he was defeated
by Lee in the party's nomination race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
