<HEADLINE> Premier Calls for Help to Developing Countries in Cleaning Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today
called on big Western international firms to help solve developing
countries' environmental problems by offering them financial
support.
</P>
<P>
Li made the call during a meeting with foreign delegates who
are attending a four-day China Environmental Forum which opened at
the Great Hall of the People here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 international environmentalists including former
Australian Prime Minister P.J. Keating and former Dutch Prime
Minister R.F.N. Lubbers as well as representatives from some big
western industrial and financial firms are attending the forum.
</P>
<P>
"I hope those powerful international businesses will provide
financial support to developing countries to help them dealing
with environmental problems while showing concerns for their own
problems at home," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China welcomes international environmentalists to
strengthen their environmental cooperation with their Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"Environmental protection is not only the work of the
government, but also demands the participation of all sectors of
the society including enterprises and non-governmental
organizations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the environmental protection as the basic
national policy of the country, he said, "the Chinese government
pays great attention to this work and has made big achievements."
</P>
<P>
"But on the other hand, we must keep a clear mind on the
environmental problems that do exist in China," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country, China will do whatever it can to
protect its environment while developing its economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the country's energy policy, the Chinese premier
said that China lays equal stress on both developing and saving
energy.
</P>
<P>
"China will gradually increase the consumption of clean energy
while reducing the use of coal," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China will also make more efforts to solve its problems of
soil erosion and pollution caused by small enterprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin and Director of the State
Administration of Environment Xie Zhenhua were present at the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
