<HEADLINE> HK Future Teachers Receive Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China, today awarded certificates to 2,782 graduates from the Hong
Kong Institute of Education (HKIEd).
</P>
<P>
This was the third graduation ceremony of the institute, which
was established in 1994 to produce qualified teachers for Hong
Kong's kindergartens, primary and secondary schools, technical
schools and schools for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony held at the Queen Elizabeth Stadium,
Professor Ruth Hayhoe, director of the institute, extended her
congratulations to the graduates and wished them the very best in
their new professional careers.
</P>
<P>
She elaborated on two main themes: the new expectations of
teachers and the new opportunities open to the teaching profession
as a result of the Chief Executive's Policy Address on October 8.
</P>
<P>
Education has been given a place of honor in the policy
framework which Tung has put forward for Hong Kong's future
development, Hayhoe said.
</P>
<P>
September 10 has been named Teachers Day, following a precedent
in China's mainland and it will be a day when everyone shows their
respect for the work of teachers, and their recognition of the
special way that teachers' professional knowledge contributes to
the health and prosperity of society, she added.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation that all new teachers entering the profession
are expected to be university graduates and professionally
trained, the challenge for HKIEd's certificate of education
graduates will be to continue their studies and reach the level of
a Bachelor of Education, Hayhoe said.
</P>
<P>
They have to continue improving their language skills in
speaking and writing English and Chinese, she said.
</P>
<P>
Also they will be expected to make extensive use of information
technology in the classrooms for the benefit of their students,
Hayhoe added.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, the first after Hong Kong's return to China,
Hayhoe asked students of Hong Kong to explore and learn from their
rich cultural heritage, to share with colleagues and friends in
the mainland their many positive experiences and in the process
open their minds to new areas of understanding.
</P>
<P>
"You have an exciting challenge ahead of you -- to develop each
of the pupils in your classes to their fullest potential, in a
context where they will be expected to be responsible citizens of
Hong Kong and of the Mainland, also to be citizens of the world,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was attended by 3,500 students and academic staff,
parents, guests from the Government and the education sector as
well as community leaders from all walks of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
