<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Group Responsible for Luxor Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's most powerful extremist
group today claimed responsibility for the deadly attack on
foreign tourists that claimed 68 lives in southern Egypt on Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
In a statement faxed to international news agencies, Gamaa
Islamia, or the Islamic Group, said the gunmen killed the tourists
while trying to take them hostage.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier statement, the Islamic faction threatened that
the Luxor killing, which was aimed at warning the tourists who
come to Egypt, would not be the last and more violent attacks will
be coming.
</P>
<P>
Six gunmen opened fire randomly at foreign tourists and
Egyptians in front of the Hatsheput Temple in Luxor, about 500
kilometers south of Cairo. At least 24 were wounded. This was the
worst terrorist shooting attack ever happened in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group has been leading a terror wave since 1992
against Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's secular government to
install a strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
One of the six gunmen has been identified as a group member
who had committed other terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting the scene of the crime this morning, Mubarak
condemned the killers as "murderers" and "criminals" who have no
religion whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
"They do not belong to any faith whether Islam, Christianity or
Judaism," he said, while trying to reassure potential visitors
that Egypt is still safe.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of heavily-armed police guarded the site today as around
50 courageous foreign tourists ventured into 4,500-year-old
Hatsheput Temple.
</P>
<P>
Seven of those injured in the Luxor attack, including five
Swiss, a Japanese and an Egyptian, are in serious condition after
receiving treatment at Maadi Hospital, Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The police have identified up to 51 ill-fated foreigners - 31
Swiss, eight Japanese, four British, five German, a Bulgarian, a
French and a Colombian.
</P>
<P>
The killed Egyptians include two policemen, a security guard
and a worker of the antiquities authority. The six terrorists were
gunned down by the police on the site.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 people, mostly police, Christian Coptics and
foreign tourists, have been killed in the Islamic extremists'
five-year violent campaign against the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
