<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Government, Central Bank Differ over Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Finance and
Economy (MOFE) and the central Bank of Korea (BOK) are at odds
over the introduction of emergency loans from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to stabilize the protracted currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is facing a serious shortage of foreign exchanges,
with the local currency won racing to renew its record lows
against the dollar day after day.
</P>
<P>
Most MOFE officials assert that the nation's economy can
overcome the current turmoil without the IMF bailout. They
stressed that the IMF rescue package, which has a string of
conditions, could drive the national economy to bankruptcy and
infringe upon economic sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
As one of the policy options, the government is reportedly
pushing the BOK to borrow more than 10 billion U.S. dollars from
foreign banks, including the U.S. Federal Reserve Board and the
Bank of International Settlement (BIS).
</P>
<P>
"Through various measures, the ministry aims to raise the
nation's foreign currency reserves from the current level of less
than 30 billion dollars to 38 billion," a MOFE official noted.
</P>
<P>
However, South Korean banks, suffering from their declining
credit rates, found it impossible to borrow from abroad and
difficult to lend foreign currencies to businesses.
</P>
<P>
BOK officials recommended the government to apply for emergency
IMF loans as the most effective way to ease the foreign exchange
crunch.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, central bank governor Lee Kyung-shik
today held a meeting with the presidents from eight commercial and
state-run banks, including Korea First Bank and Korea Development
Bank, to discuss ways of easing the currency woes.
</P>
<P>
They reportedly decided to request the government to take IMF
bailout loans as a sole way to tide over the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of economists here also said that the IMF
emergency loans ranging from 30 to 50 billion dollars will be the
ultimate solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
