<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Takes U.S. to WTO Over Export Subsidy Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
announced that it is taking a United States subsidy scheme to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) for formal consultations.
</P>
<P>
The commission is requesting an end to the so-called scheme of
"Foreign Sales Corporations (FSCs)", which is only available if a
large part of the exported item has been manufactured in the U.S.,
the commission's vice-president Sir Leon Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government grants tax exemptions for exports conducted
through FSCs, that are usually subsidiaries of U.S. corporations
located in such tax havens as the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, therefore, views it a clear violation
of the WTO subsidy rules.
</P>
<P>
"The FSCs scheme clearly breaks the WTO rules and distorts
international trade by giving U.S. companies an unfair advantage
over their European competitors," the vice-president said.
</P>
<P>
Export subsidies, which favor exports compared with the
treatment of like products when sold for domestic consumption, are
prohibited under the WTO Agreement on Subsidies and Countervailing
Measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
