<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras to Lead U.S. Team against Swedes in Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras will spearhead the
U.S. team to challeng Sweden in the Davis Cup final next week.
</P>
<P>
Jonas Bjorkman will lead a Swedish team that also includes
Magnus Larsson, Thomas Enqvist and Nicklas Kulti for the
Nov. 28-30 final in Goteborg, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
U.S. captain Tom Gullikson is expected to select Sampras and
Michael Chang for the singles, with Bjorkman and Enqvist playing
singles for Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's top doubles pairing is Bjorkman and Kulti. Todd Martin
is expected to play doubles for the Americans with either Sampras
or Alex O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
Sampras beat Bjorkman in straight sets last week in the
semifinals of the ATP World Championship in Hanover, Germany, to
extend his career record against the Swede to 7-1. But Bjorkman,
ranked No. 4 in the world, beat Chang earlier in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
Sampras went on to defeat Yevgeny Kafelknikov in the Hanover
final to cap another exceptional season and finish as No. 1 for
the fifth year in a row.
</P>
<P>
Sampras led the United States to the Davis Cup title in 1995,
accounting for all three points _ two in singles and one in
doubles _ in the 3-2 victory over Russia in the final in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The United States leads Sweden 7-2 in Davis Cup play. The
countries have met only once before in the final, with Sweden
winning 4-1 in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The United States, appearing in its 59th Davis Cup final, has
won the title 31 times. Sweden, in its 11th final, has won five
titles and was runner-up to France last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Unveils Economic Stimulation Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government today
announced a package of pump-priming measures to revive the economy
through deregulation and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The package, which contains 120 measures, is intended to
stimulate the financial, real estate, media, transportation and
welfare sectors and lend support to small and medium-sized
companies.
</P>
<P>
To uplift the capital markets, the government will submit bills
to the next Diet (parliament) session to pave way for the trading
in equity derivatives and market deregulation.
</P>
<P>
Banks and insurance firms will be allowed to deal in mutual
funds and brokerage houses to diversify their operations.
</P>
<P>
On tax reform, the government will review the systems of
corporate tax, land tax and monetary- and securities-related taxes
during the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
To foster the media industry, the package will lift the
restrictions on the number of multi-channel programs that are
available via satellite. A bill will also be introduced to
encourage competition in telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
By focusing on deregulation and structural reforms, the
government hopes to pump new life into private and corporate
activities and to wipe out lingering uncertainties about the
economy, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
"A recovery of confidence will have a positive impact on the
economy," said an official from the Economic Planning Agency (EPA).
</P>
<P>
However, economists reacted negatively to the government move,
arguing that the package will neither have a resuscitating impact
on the sluggish economy nor promote structural economic reform.
</P>
<P>
This is the government's first set of pump-priming measures
since April 1995, when concerns about deflation peaked with the
U.S. dollar briefly falling below 80 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
