<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan's Free Economic Zone Sees Impressive Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bishkek Free Economic
Zone in Kyrgyzstan has experienced a remarkable economic growth
since its establishment two years ago, a Kazakh business weekly
reported today.
</P>
<P>
With a monthly output value of six million U.S. dollars, the
zone now accounts for 5 percent of that country's gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Investors in the zone, which lies on the outskirts of the
Kyrgyz capital of Bishkek, enjoy a variety of preferential
treatment in taxation, production and land use.
</P>
<P>
Within two years, a total of 120 enterprises have been
established there, including 100 wholly foreign-owned and joint
venture businesses. They produce daily necessities, medicines,
packaging and building materials, communications equipment and
processed farm products.
</P>
<P>
First investors were mainly from Turkey and China, but
businessmen from the United States, Germany, France, the
Netherlands and Israel are beginning to rush in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
