<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton Administration is offering to allow Iraq to buy
more goods with its oil, finding itself forced to retreat from its
refusal to negotiate with Saddam Hussein. The offer -- cobbled
together as a position paper by British and American diplomats --
was passed to France and Russia, who were to discuss it with the
Iraqis, officials said.
</P>
<P>
-- The Democratic Peopole's Republic of Korea appears ready to
start serious negotiations on a formal end to the Korean War,
replacing an armistice put in place 44 years ago with a peace
treaty, a senior U.S. State Department official said. Four-party
talks among diplomats from DPRK, South Korea, the United States
and China would begin sometime next month in Geneva after a
preliminary meeting in New York on Friday, the official said.
</P>
