<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Debt Reaches 117.3 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign debt until
September this year reached 117.3 billion U.S. dollars and the
country's total debt service ratio by the end of fiscal year
1997-98 is expected to reach 34.5 percent, a senior official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debt consisted of 52.3 billion dollars in
government loans and 65 billion dollars in private loans, Finance
Minister Mar'ie Muhammad told House Commission VIII on the state
budget and finance.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has been monitoring the acquisition of
loans through reports on debts worth at least one million U.S.
dollars, including basic data, variables as well as the securing
of the loans.
</P>
<P>
"We have to control our foreign loans to reduce the burden that
has been weighing on our balance of payment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has yet to decide whether Indonesia will
give prepayments for its high-interest foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
"The repayment of out foreign debt will depend on the rupiah's
recovery against the U.S. dollar," he said, adding that if the
rupiah continues to depreciate until next year, the country's
ability to repay the principal and interest of its foreign loans
will surely be affected.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah has dropped by more than 40 percent
against the U.S. dollar this year, especially following the
monetary crisis in the Southeast Asian region since early July.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that Indonesia's capital inflow in the
second semester of 1997-98 reached 3.4 billion dollars from
foreign loans under the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI)
while bilateral loans from CGI member countries reached 54
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
