<HEADLINE> Qatar, Canada Agree on Methanol Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Qatari and Canadian
petrochemical companies today signed a memorandum of understanding
for setting up a methanol plant costing 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The plant, when completed, was expected to have an annual
production capacity of 3 million tonnes of methanol.
</P>
<P>
The Qatar General Petroleum Corporation (QGPC) would take 51
percent of the shares and the Methanex Corporation (CEO) of
Canada, a world leading company in Methanol business, would have
the rest.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Qatari Minister of Energy and
Industry Abdullah Bin Hamad Al-Attiya for the QGPC and CEO
Chairman Pierre Choquette on the sidelines of the on-going Middle
East and North Africa economic conference.
</P>
<P>
The QGPC also reached another 1-billion-dollar agreement with
the Mobil Corporation here Monday on a project to extract gas from
the world's largest gas field in northern Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The project would produce 1 billion cubic feet of gas per day
which would primarily meet the needs of Qatari domestic market.
</P>
