<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beats Japan 3-1 at World Grand Champions Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HIROSHIMA, Japan, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Asian Champion China
proved its depth by downing Japan 3-0 in the world volleyball
continental grand champions cup here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first victory for the Chinese women spikers through
three rounds after lossing to Russia 3-0 and Cuba 3-2 earlier.
</P>
<P>
China took the first set with an easy win of 15-4, but the
hosts tied it at 1-1 with a spectacular defensive effort from
1.59-meter tall setter Takeshita Yoshie from the bench.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Takeshia, a genius in back-row defence, also
showed her talent in setting up the attackings for Japan. But she
soon found it was difficult to repeat it in the third set when her
taller counterpart Zhu Yunzhi, also 19, but stood at 1.76-meter,
paced China to clinch the set in 15-13.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yunying, who replaced China's starting setter He Qi in the
middle of the second set, kept her place in the remaining times
and helped China seal the win 15-8 in the fourth set.
</P>
<P>
In the other two matches played earlier on Tuesday, Olympic and
world champions Cuba remained unbeaten by overwhelming South Korea
3-0, while Russia also boosted their winning streak by downing
Brazil 3-2.
</P>
<P>
The taller and powerful Cubans spikers, although made many
serving errors in the first set, used their over-net smashings and
blockings to sink their not-in-form South Korean opponents 15-8,
15-10, 15-2.
</P>
<P>
European champion Russia overcame a slow start and outspiked the
South American champion Brazil 7-15, 15-7, 9-15, 15-7, 15-10 for
their third win in as many games so far in the six-team tournaments.
</P>
<P>
"Today's match was much tougher than I had expected," said Russian
head coach Nicola Karpol. "I hope our players will get accustomed to
the circumstances in Japan and concentrate more on the following
games."
</P>
<P>
The Russia-Brazil game lasted for one hour and 47 minutes, the
longest since last Friday, the opening day of the 12-day
tournament. The tourney has applied a 25-minute time limitation
for the first four sets and a rally-point scoring system in the
fifth set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
