<HEADLINE> Islamic Group in Egypt Threatens More Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- As Egyptian leaders condemned
the rampage killers of foreign tourists in a southern resort as
"murderers" and "criminals", an extremist Islamic faction today
threatened that more violent attacks will be coming.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Middle East News Agency, the Gamaa
Islamia, or the Islamic Group, said that the Luxor killing, which
was aimed at warning the tourists who come to Egypt, would not
be the last.
</P>
<P>
Six unidentified gunmen killed more than 60 foreign tourists
and Egyptians Monday in random shootings in Luxor, about 500
kilometers south of Cairo. This was the worst terrorist shooting
attack ever happened in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The group suspected of masterminding the incident and other
violence since 1992, however, did not claim responsibility for the
attack in its statement.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting the scene of the crime this morning, Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak condemned the killers as "murderers" and
"criminals" who have no religion whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
"They do not belong to any faith whether Islam, Christianity or
Judaism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Extremist Islamic militants have been staging a campaign to
topple the secular government for strict Islamic rule, which has
claimed more than 1,300 people, mostly police, Christians and
foreign tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
