<HEADLINE> EU Plans to Make De-Mining Safer, Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
decided to launch a research program aimed at using new
technologies to make de-mining safer and faster.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made known today, was taken at the initiative of
Commissioner Edith Cresson who is responsible for research,
innovation, education, training and youth.
</P>
<P>
The program will be given a total of 15 million ECU (17 million
U.S. dollars) in its pursuit of new technologies for seeking,
identifying and deactivating landmines.
</P>
<P>
The planned research activities will focus on the real needs of
de-mining operations.
</P>
<P>
New technologies can make a vital contribution, particularly by
improving minefield surveys, analysing data from multiple sensors
to detect and identify individual mines, using geographical
information database to collate and store all information
available on minefields and in mine removal, according to an EU
press release.
</P>
<P>
An estimated total of 125 million uncleared anti-personnel and
anti-tank mines are laid in former theaters of war around the
world, killing more than 26,000 people, mostly children, each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
