<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Revises Property Market Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government
announced today that it has decided to review its policies on the
property market, so as to "avoid aggravating the excess supply and
pessimistic sentiment in the property market".
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a press conference chaired by
Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who announced the
government policy adjustments in May 1996 to curb the excessive
speculative activities in the property market then.
</P>
<P>
The reviewed measures announced today include deferring the
government's land sale program and extending the project
completion period, currently set at four to five years for
residential sale sites, to eight years.
</P>
<P>
The government will also suspend the stamp duty surcharge
payable on properties sold within three years of purchase, a
measure introduced in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government said that these reviewed measures will help ease
the excess supply in the market. However, the government also made
it clear that it will not stimulate demand for properties by
relaxing credit, for example, by raising the 80 percent limit on
mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
This would be imprudent from the point of view of both the
buyers and the financial institutions, especially at this time of
economic uncertainty, it said.
</P>
<P>
The government stressed that a healthy and stable property
market is important to the economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
By moderating the supply of new land for private housing and
allowing greater flexibility for the supply of new projects to
adjust to demand, the property market can self-correct and buffer
against volatile prices, the government said.
</P>
<P>
The government said that the package of measures introduced in
May 1996 to cool the speculative frenzy stabilized the market and
averted a property bubble. However, today the situation and market
sentiment had totally changed.
</P>
<P>
Property prices have been gradually declining since May 1996,
the government noted, adding that in the third quarter of this
year, the sales of uncompleted private residential properties fell
to 1,376 units, 22 percent lower than the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, property prices declined by 4.4 percent in the
three-month period, the sharpest fall since May 1996, the
government observed and pointed out that "the market is now in an
excess supply situation".
</P>
<P>
Announcing the new adjustments, the government stressed that
the measures are not intended to fix property prices at any
particular level.
</P>
<P>
"They are to take into account the regional economic
uncertainties and avoid aggravating the excess supply and
pessimistic sentiments in the property market", it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
