<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Scientific Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A Resurs-F1M scientific
satellite was launched today by a Soyuz-U booster from
Plesetsk cosmodrome in north Russia, the Interfax news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite was designed for making photographs of the
surface of the earth for Russian civilian agencies, according to
the press service of the Strategic Missile Force.
</P>
<P>
Resurs is equipped with a landing capsule and reusable
photo cameras. The 6.3 tonne satellite is to remain in orbit for
25 days, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The first satellite in the series was launched in
September 1979 and the latest in August 1993. 
</P>
