<HEADLINE> Australian Indigenous Health Depressing: Governor- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian Governor-General
William Deane today called on international health experts to
share their knowledge with the Australian medical community to
improve what he called the "extremely depressing" condition of
aboriginal health in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The governor-general told the 30th International Hospital
Federation Congress in Melbourne that Australia was one of the
healthiest nations in the world with one important exception:
indigenous health.
</P>
<P>
He said the life expectancy of an Aboriginal baby was almost 20
years less than a non-aboriginal child.
</P>
<P>
"These facts are extremely depressing. The problems of
aboriginal health are devastating in their extent," the
governor-general was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He told the health experts to share their knowledge with
Australian colleagues "to improve substantially the health of the
aboriginal people."
</P>
<P>
There are about 300,000 indigenous people in Australia.
</P>
<P>
At an earlier engagement today, the governor-general urged
Australians to address the plight of the disadvantaged, adding
that aborigines were "the most disadvantaged group in Australia."
</P>
<P>
The plight of the disadvantaged, along with reconciliation,
would be the biggest test for Australia as it entered its second
century of federation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor-general, a ceremonial political figure in
Australia, has spoken on several occasions for the country's
disadvantaged indigenous people in the past several months.
</P>
</TEXT>
