<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- British travel companies
have started an airlift today to bring hundreds of UK
tourists back from Egypt after a gun attack left scores of
visitors dead on Monday, according to press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Seven aircraft left Britain this morning bound for
Luxor, the southern Egyptian resort, to evacuate Britons who
want to cut their holidays short after the massacre. They
are expected to return this evening, said an airport
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at Manchester, four special flights from Egypt
will land tonight.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that tour flights to Egypt due to depart
in the next few days have been all cancelled and a verdict
on later flights is still awaited.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Foreign Office has confirmed that six Britons
were among some 70 people who died in the massacre by
suspected Moslem militants.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook Monday condemned the
gun attack as "sickening act of violence" and Prime Minister
Tony Blair also called Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to
send his condolences and express solidarity in fighting
aginst terrorism.  
