<HEADLINE> Nigerians Express Cautious Welcome to Abacha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerians have expressed
cautious welcome to the Head of State, General Sani Abacha's
Monday speech marking his fourth anniversary in power.
</P>
<P>
The Nigeria's Tribune today reported that the country's five
political parties have applauded the dissolution of the cabinet,
saying that it would rejuvenate confidence and interest in the
remaining elections in the transition period.
</P>
<P>
On the formation of the new cabinet, the report said the party
leaders have called for a transitional government genuinely
concerned with preparing the nation for the democratic government
expected to be put in place next October.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Lawan Gambo, National Chairman of the Grassroots
Democratic Movement, reportedly said that the new cabinet should
be made up of "every sector of the polity including the political
parties".
</P>
<P>
Solomon Onaghinon, Secretary-General of the Association of
Senior Civil Servants of Nigeria said that there is no cause
for euphoria right now, because the dissolution of the cabinet
did not explain the direction of the government.
</P>
<P>
"The action in the next couple of days would dictate the real
state of things," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's announcement of the release of political detainees
received almost unanimous welcome.
</P>
<P>
Bode Olajumoke, the National Deputy Chairman of the United
Nigeria Congress Party said that he commends the initiative of the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
But again people are cautious, as the names of the detainees
to be freed are yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Sorunke, a traditional ruler in the Ogun, home
state of Boshorun Abiola, the presumed winner of the 1993
presidential election now in detention, commented with a proverb,
"Somebody whose son killed an elephant said 'I can't believe it,
until I eat it.'" 
</P>
