<HEADLINE> Cost of New Airport Projects Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Budget for the Airport Core
Programs (ACP) has been reduced further by more than one billion
HK dollars (128 million US dollars) thanks to tight control of
cost.
</P>
<P>
So far, the overall cost for the ten ACP projects centering on
Chek Lap Kok New Airport has declined to 155.3 billion HK dollars
(20 billion US dollars), according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time the budget has been cut, adding that the
total amount reduced to 8.4 billion HK dollars (1.1 billion US
dollars), about 5.1 percent of the original estimate of 163.7
billion HK dollars (21.1 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Billy Lam Chung-lun, director of the New Airport Projects
Co-ordination Office (NAPCO), attributed the successful cut in
budget to cost control and effective claim settlement.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the third quarter this year, the overall ACP was
90 percent complete, said the official. Eight out of the ten
projects have been finished, including expressways, bridges, land
reclamation programs, and a harbor crossing.
</P>
<P>
Two others are scheduled to be completed next year -- the New
Airport now under construction on a small island in the west of
Hong Kong, and a railway to link the airport with Kowloon and Hong
Kong Island. The New Airport is expected to go into operation in
April, 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
