<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Campaigns Against Growing Rat Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Alarmed by raging rat
activities in the Chinese capital, Beijing's public health
authorities have called on residents to take an active part in the
campaign to rid the city of the rodent.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government ordered a unified distribution of rat
poison last weekend in the city on a scale described as the
largest in the last 10 years, according to today's Beijing Daily.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yubing, head of Beijing's Patriotic Campaign Committee
which is responsible for monitoring pest control, said the rat
population has been on the rise in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Rat density has exceeded the state-set tolerable line in rural
areas, conjunctive parts between urban and rural areas and in old
buildings torn down for reconstruction," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Rats have become a common sight in Beijing, running across the
streets even during daytime. They have damaged telephone and power
lines and spoiled grains. Some big hotels are complaining of rats
chewing tourists' clothes and even "stealing" their false teeth.
</P>
<P>
"Rampant rat activities have posed threats to people's health,
their normal work and production activities," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
One health official warned of epidemics caused by rats since
some bordering countries reportedly have been invaded by rat-bite
fever and other plagues among animals and human beings in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Experts said one reason for the growing rat population is the
drastic decrease in the last 10 years of the number of owls and
weasels, natural predators of rats.
</P>
<P>
Also, cats are now kept not to catch mice but as pets.
</P>
<P>
"There is a break in biological chains," said Wang Chengxin, a
professor with the China Academy of Preventive Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
So far, Beijing has distributed 300,000 leaflets among
residents calling for their immediate participation. Meanwhile,
about 250 tons of poison bait has been put in places frequented by
rats such as public green areas, sewers, restaurants and meat and
vegetable markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0167 </DOCNO>
