<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunlight Causes Eye Cataracts: Australian Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- An Australian researcher
said today his new study had bolstered the theory that sunlight
causes eye cataracts.
</P>
<P>
Minas Coroneo, a researcher with University of New South Wales
(UNSW) in Australia, said his study also raised questions about
the usefulness of most sunglasses, the Australian Associated Press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Professor Coroneo, head of ophthalmology at UNSW, said he had
shown that most damage was caused by ultra-violet (UV) light
hitting the periphery of the eye.
</P>
<P>
It was immediately refocused to the opposite side, closest to
the nose, he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the very spot where cataracts develop, and also the
site for pterygia, growth which afflicts thousands of Australians,
particularly those from hot, dry environments, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
Coroneo told the Royal Australian College of Ophthalmology
conference in Sydney that he had proved the link by examining the
eyes of people with pterygia, after death.
</P>
<P>
He found tissue damage inside the eyes underneath the pterygia,
which coincided with the area where light is refocused.
</P>
<P>
For children, Coroneo recommends broad-brimmed hats only,
because sunglasses with wings may interfere with the development
of a natural protective mechanism in which the lens of the eye
becomes tinted with age.
</P>
<P>
Cataracts are common among welders, who despite protective
masks tend to receive large doses of UV rays in the periphery of
their vision from other workers, the professor said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> External Debt Drains COMESA Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The bulk of export earnings by
member states of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) is being drained through repayment of the over 80
billion U.S. Dollars external debts, according to Zambia's
vice-president Godfrey Miyanda.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency ZANA today quoted Miyanda as saying here
Monday at the first COMESA Finance Ministers Meeting that the
regional grouping should negotiate jointly for relief of the debt
to halt capital flight and redress the distortion of their
economies.
</P>
<P>
"The major problem that faces all our economies is that of the
debt," said the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the regional community had by 1994 owed
the international community at least 88 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda told the three-day meeting starting Monday that it
will not be feasible for the people in the COMESA region to enjoy
the benefits of economic liberalization being pursued as long as
the current drain on export earnings continued through servicing
of external debt.
</P>
<P>
He called for the consolidation of COMESA financial
institutions to enhance monetary and financial cooperation. This
will also help to expedite the integration process through the
merging of markets for goods, services, capital and labor, said
Miyanda.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers are meeting to revise the implementation
of the COMESA monetary harmonization program.
</P>
<P>
Top of their agenda includes the future role of the clearing
house whose original functions are said to have been overtaken by
the new economic regimes in most member countries.
</P>
<P>
The clearing house, which is now an autonomous body, was set
up in the 1980s as an important sector of the preferential trade
area for eastern and southern Africa, predecessor of the COMESA,
to mitigate the economic environment then that had been
characterized by controls, particularly of foreign exchange
outflows from most member states.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA that came into being in 1994 groups 20 members and
aims to achieve a free trade area by 2000, a customs union with a
zero tariff on products originating within the common market and
free movement of capital and people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
