<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Official Calls for Consensus on Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo today urged delegates to an "Asian Fund
Facility" meeting here to reach consensus on a workable framework
for regional cooperation in dealing with or preventing a financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the Finance and Central Bank
Deputies Meeting on the Asian Fund Facility, de Ocampo, chairman
of the conference, said: "The ongoing economic turbulence in
Southeast Asia poses a major challenge to all of us in the
region."
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interest not only of economies in Southeast Asia,
but of the whole world that we address the issues that have merged
from this currency crisis not only to solve it and regain investor
confidence in the region but also to prevent a crisis like this
one from recurring in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He requested the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to provide
an in-depth analysis of the financial crisis that has prevailed in
Southeast Asia since July this year.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said that the challenge of the meeting is to "reach
consensus on a workable framework for regional cooperation."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the framework should include at least the
following elements:
</P>
<P>
-- A mechanism for regional surveillance to complement the
global surveillance efforts of the IMF;
</P>
<P>
-- Enhancement of economic and technical cooperation to
strengthen the supervision and regulation of financial and capital
markets; and
</P>
<P>
-- Supplemental financing mechanism on a quick-response,
self-help, good neighbor philosophy to augment IMF resources.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, the participants are expected to
discuss the need for a quick-response supplemental financing
facility linked to IMF conditionalities, ways to address the moral
hazard problem, guiding principles and mechanics of the proposed
fund, and regional surveillance and economic cooperation
mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Fund was proposed by Japan at the joint IMF-World
Bank annual meeting in Hong Kong in September, but the United
States initially gave a lukewarm response.
</P>
<P>
Other industrialized nations have resisted Japan's idea of an
independent "Asian Monetary Fund," as they fear that an
independent fund would undermine the IMF conditions attached to
its economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
An IMF official said here Monday that a "broad consensus" has
been reached among countries involved on how the fund should be
structured to help countries suffering economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the opening of the meeting, Philippine Finance
Secretary de Ocampo told a press conference that preliminary
soundings "seem to focus on ASEAN (becoming core members and
contributors to the fund) because that is where the crisis started
 and that is where the contagion effect has spread."
</P>
<P>
Other countries could be joined at participatory level or
contributing level, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The initial deliberations are less in favor of a large pool of
funds" that would call for the establishment of a bureaucracy to
manage it, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Whether there may be a fund at all of a smaller size," he
said. "I leave it to the (participants) to elaborate upon."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed earlier that progress made at the Manila meeting
will serve as valuable inputs to the APEC leaders when they meet
in Vancouver, Canada, on November 24-25 and discuss the Asian
currency situation.
</P>
<P>
The framework proposed at the Manila meeting would also be
discussed at the informal ASEAN finance ministers meeting in Kuala
Lumpur on December 1, he said.
</P>
<P>
If agreed by the ministers, de Ocampo said, such framework
could be presented to the ASEAN Leaders Meeting in Kuala Lumpur on
December 15-16 for their approval.
</P>
<P>
Deputy finance ministers and deputy central bank governors from
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations), Japan, the United
States, South Korea, China and other Asian-Pacific nations
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the IMF, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank were also present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
