<HEADLINE> Undersupply of Wool May Be Coming: Australian Wool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Wool growers, presently
sitting on a 700 million US dollar stockpile, could face a new
challenge of demand exceeding supply, Australia's key wool body
predicted today.
</P>
<P>
"Signs are there that demand for wool is picking up, albeit
gradually in most markets," Adrian Kloeden, managing director of
the International Wool Secretariat, said.
</P>
<P>
"In not too many years, our problem may well be under-supply,"
he told the Wool Forum in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"The management of the transition from our current situation to
that of coping with supply shortages will be one of our main
challenges as an industry."
</P>
<P>
Australian wool growers have spent more than a decade living
with a stockpile, which at its peak in the late 1980s was four
million bales and is now 1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
Kloeden, who is also managing director of the Australian Wool
Research and Promotion Organization, said wool exports rose by 13
percent this year, with big increases coming from China and Italy.
</P>
<P>
He said future strong demand was expected from China, Britain
and North America, but demand in European markets would pick up
only slowly.
</P>
<P>
The industry would also suffer the "knock-on effects" of the
Asian currency crisis, which might delay the industry's recovery.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
