<HEADLINE> No S. African Found in Luxor Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Embassy
officials in Cairo were checking hotels this morning in the
southern Egyptian town of Luxor to establish whether any South
Africans needed help in the wake of Monday's massacre that killed
67 people.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian authorities has told South African ambassador, Justus
de Goede, that so far no South Africans were found among the dead
or injured, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said embassy staff were making telephone checks
with hotels in Luxor. Yet no South Africans appeared to be
holidaying there.
</P>
<P>
The embassy wanted to make direct contact with any South
African nationals in case help was required.
</P>
<P>
With four flights a week to Cairo from South Africa, about
30,000 to 45,000 South Africans arrive in Egypt every year,
according to Egyptian authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, de Goede said most were en route to other
destinations and only a fairly small percentage stay in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The embassy had not received any panic calls from South
Africans and was still trying to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
On whether the South African government would issue a travel
warning, he said: "We're checking, we want to assess the
situation. After yesterday's chaos a fuller picture is starting
to form."
</P>
<P>
There were no plans to evacuate South Africans, the embassy
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said in Pretoria that
the department had fielded a significant number of calls from
concerned South Africans whose family members were visiting
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
About 50 calls had been received since news of the massacre
first broke, spokesman Marco Boni said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-seven people, 60 of whom were tourists, were gunned down
by 10 armed Islamic militants in a 45-minute killing spree in
Luxor Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead were European and Japanese tourists.
</P>
<P>
The Jamaa Islamiya, which Egyptian police said left messages
claiming responsibility for the attack, is Egypt's main armed
Islamic group.
</P>
<P>
It has waged an armed campaign since 1992 seeking to overthrow
the government of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and establish
a fundamentalist Islamic state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
