<HEADLINE> Foreign Money Flows into Kenya at Slower Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital is flowing
into Kenya's stock market at a slower rate than earlier this
year, according to the latest Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE)
monthly report.
</P>
<P>
The net inflow of foreign money rose to 105.2 million
Shillings (1.65 million U.S. Dollars) last month from the 95.4
million Shillings net inflow in September, but remained well
below June's peak of 331.9 million Shillings, said the NSE
report.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign turnover in October was 145.775 million
Shillings or 36.3 percent of Kenyan stock market's total turnover
from 135.841 million Shillings or 27.5 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi bourse slid in August following the suspension of
205-million-Dollar aid package by the International Monetary Fund
to Kenya on the grounds of corruption and governance issues. The
Shilling depreciated immediately due to the aid halt.
</P>
<P>
However, the weaker Shilling at around 63.80 to the Dollar
Monday, compared to around 55 in July, means the market is
cheaper for offshore investors.
</P>
<P>
Foreign participation was concentrated in the industrial
sector, which accounted for 52 percent of total foreign turnover
in October.
</P>
<P>
The commercial sector accounted for 28 percent, agriculture 16
percent and financials just four percent, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The most highly traded share by all investors was Kenya Power
Lighting. Its turnover increased to 101 million Shillings in
October from 50 million Shillings in September.
</P>
<P>
The NSE 20-share index lost 132 points to close at 3,314.84 at
the end of October from 3,447.41 in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
