<HEADLINE> US to Move Ties With Pakistan to New Level: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting US Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said here today that the US wanted to
move its relations with Pakistan to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here last night for a 20-hour visit,
called on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif this morning. She said the
Clinton Administration was seeking a substantive improvement in
its relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Foreign Ministry, Sharif said on
the occasion that it would be his personal endeavor to improve and
cement the relationship with the US.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the policies pursued by his government
to bring economic prosperity to the country and to contribute to
the peace and stability in the region are conducive to
strengthening Pak-US relations.
</P>
<P>
"We want the US to take advantage of the investment and
commercial opportunities in Pakistan and become our partner in
progress and development," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Albright agreed with Sharif, saying the US wanted to move the
economic and commercial relations to the center of the bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed the need for an early resolution of the F-16
issue, the removal of remaining Pressler Amendment restrictions
and full implementation of the Brown Amendment so that the
relationship between Pakistan and the US could be freed from
restraints of the past.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the long-running Afghan crisis.
Sharif stressed that Pakistan had no favorites in Afghanistan and
had been in contact with all the Afghan groups in a bid to
facilitate the intra-Afghan dialogue under the UN.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit to Pakistan is the first by a US secretary of
state in 14 years. She is also expected to visit India and
Bangladesh after her Pakistani tour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
