<HEADLINE> Rains Kill Teenager, Damage Bridges in E. and W. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Rains hit eastern and western
Uganda, killing a teenager and damaging roads and bridges in
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Anani Wonasolo, 18, was killed by a huge stone in a landslide
in Nabekye village, Sisilyi sub-county in eastern Mbale district,
and Miria Nabuduwa, his sister, was injured on the waist, legs
and chest, Jerome Baryaga, a policeman in the district, told The
New Vision.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains were hitting the district from November 14,
an earlier report said. A new report reaching here said up to 500
acres of wheat worth of 200 millions of Uganda shillings (some
200,000 u.s. dollars) was devastated in Sebei Elgon cooperative
union alone.
</P>
<P>
In Kapchorwa district in the east, Charles Opio, the resident
commissioner of the district, asked local residents to keep the
roads passable yesterday in his office for bussinessmen to
transport maize out of the district. Many roads and bridges were
damaged in the district. Maize is one of the main crops in the
district. Torrential rains from November 8 made the roads in the
district very difficult to pass, and that caused the decreasing
of price of crops, an earlier report said.
</P>
<P>
In Iganga, still another eastern district, people use canoes
as transport tools instead of vehicles in flooded areas where
bridges and roads were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Western Bundibugyo district was cut off last Saturday by
landslides on the road from Bundibugyo to For Portal. The
officials from the ministry of works, transport and
communications were trying to open an alternative road to
Budibugyo town yesterday.
</P>
<P>
In western Kasese district, floods submerged 360 hectares of
cotton, maize and beans.
</P>
<P>
In another development, president Yoweri Museveni expressed
his "deep sorrow about the tragic incidents and extended the
whole country's condolences to all the families and relatives" to
victims of capsizes on Lake Albert and Lake Kioga in which a
total 36 people died. He asked for the circumstances of the
accidents. The president asked for reports about the tragedies
and improvement of security of canoes and boats on lakes.
</P>
<P>
All 18 bodies on Lake Albert have been found. Of the victims
on Lake Kyoga, three were recovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
