<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to List World Heritage Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A tentative list of
potential world heritage sites in South Africa is to be compiled
for submission to the World Heritage Center in Paris before July
next year, an official with the Department of Environmental
Affairs and Tourism said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Such sites could boost tourism in the country, while they
could also be protected by the international community, local
media quoted director of cultural resources management Makgolo
Makgolo as saying in Bloemfontein.
</P>
<P>
A site must be of universal value and be an outstanding site,
comparable to other sites in the world, before it is approved by
the World Heritage Center.
</P>
<P>
South Africa became a full member of World Heritage Convention
in October.
</P>
<P>
The list of possible sites will be discussed at a meeting of
the South African World Heritage Convention Committee in February
1998.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the first South African sites will be
approved by December 1999.
</P>
<P>
Makgolo was in Bloemfontein to conduct the first of nine
provincial workshops to identify possible sites in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Although every province has a workshop, it did not necessarily
imply that every province would have a world heritage site,
Makgolo said. There might only be about five in the whole of
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
