<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80 Survive Aborted Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- About 80 foreign passengers
survived an aborted landing Sunday night at Entebbe International
Airport, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda airline plane from Johannesburg, South Africa, was
due to land at 10:23 p.m. but as it approached the runway, it
pulled up and circled till it made the final landing at 10:34
p.m..
</P>
<P>
Charles Owor, the captain of the Flight 571, claimed after the
landing that there was a "small problem" with some landing
facilities.
</P>
<P>
But a source at the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) in Entebbe
said that control tower gave the pilot the order to go ahead to
land but the pilot seemed not ready and pulled up the plane and
landed at another runway.
</P>
<P>
The source claimed that the incident was recorded by the air
traffic controller on duty.
</P>
<P>
There was no independent commentary on the incident.
</P>
<P>
Uganda Airlines' technical services department said the pilot
had not yet given its report. There was no explanation on the
spot by the crew, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
