<HEADLINE> India to Proceed to Full Convertibility with Caution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram said on Monday that India will proceed on the road to
capital account convertibility with caution, the local press said
today.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to proceed cautiously and arrive there (full
convertibility) rather than take hasty decisions," the minister
said while meeting with a British delegation.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks when the Indian rupee touched a
21-month low against the U.S. dollar in the foreign exchange
market here.
</P>
<P>
Allaying fears of any slowdown in the reform process in the
country, Chidambaram said, "India is liberalizing and reforming at
its own pace and since the general elections last year, there has
been a number of reforms in trade policy, industrial policy and
the financial sector."
</P>
<P>
He said the United Front government has also been able to move
ahead with public sector reforms and dismantle administered price
mechanism in petroleum products. 
