<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Daily Calls on US to Accept Iraq's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian daily today called
on the United States to accept the proposal put forward by Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz to avoid another bloodshed in
the region.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, the English-language daily Tehran Times said
that the Iraqi proposal was quite sensible and rational and the
international atmosphere did not favor a military attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Even if the inevitable happens, the U.S. will not succeed to
achieve its goals since the situation of the world today is
totally different from that of 1991, it said.
</P>
<P>
The daily apparently referred to the 1991 Gulf War against
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait launched by Western-allied forces.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. political influence is on the decline, Tehran Times
noted, and "the U.S. sanctions diplomacy specially those imposed
on Iran have not only failed but have bought the U.S. the wrath
of its allies and partners."
</P>
<P>
Aziz made a proposal to the United Nations Security Council
to set up an impartial committee of experts in charge of the
U.N. inspection of Iraqi disarmament in order to end the current
crisis between Iraq and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French newspaper Le Figaro Sunday
night, Aziz said that the five permanent members of the Security
Council "should all have the same weight" and "if this formula is
accepted, we would have no objections to the return of the
American inspectors we expelled."
</P>
<P>
The crisis began after Iraq decided on October 29 to expel the
six Americans in the U.N. weapons inspection team on charge of
espionage.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion of the Americans last Thursday prompted 68
non-American members of the team to leave Iraq and triggered a
threat by the U.S. to launch military strike at Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States has dispatched more military forces to the
Persian Gulf, preparing a military attack to force Iraq to
accept the return of Americans in the U.N. inspection team.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also paid visits to
Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia over the past few days to
seek support from the Arab countries for the U.S. military attack.
</P>
<P>
Terming Albright's tour as "a total failure," the Iranian
daily Tehran Times said the trip sent a message to the U.S. that
other countries would not submit to their bullying.
</P>
<P>
The daily also called on the U.N. to play an active role in
defusing tension between Iraq and the U.S., adding that the
U.N. shoulders a great responsibility at this stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
