<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Officials Discuss Proposed Asian Fund in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Deputy finance ministers and
senior central bank officials from Asian countries and the United
States started here today a two-day meeting on the proposed Asian
Fund Facility, which would supplement IMF resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the officials are expected to discuss the need
for a quick-response supplemental financing facility linked to
International Monetary Fund (IMF) conditionalities, ways to
address the moral hazard problem, guiding principles and mechanics
of the proposed fund, and regional surveillance and economic
cooperation mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The fund was proposed by Japan at the joint IMF-World Bank
annual meeting in Hong Kong in September, but the United States
initially gave a lukewarm response.
</P>
<P>
Other industrialized nations have resisted Japan's idea of an
independent "Asian Monetary Fund," as they fear that an
independent fund would undermine the IMF conditions attached to
its economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
Bowing to pressure from the United States, Japan is reportedly
scaling back its proposal.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials said that they are now prepared to propose
alternatives that would be less ambitious than a fully independent
fund. One possibility is for Asian countries to set up a regional
emergency-rescue facility similar to the IMF's credit lines.
</P>
<P>
Credit countries would not deposit all funds on a permanent
basis as originally proposed, but would instead promise to deliver
set amounts when necessary.
</P>
<P>
An IMF official said here Monday that a "broad consensus" has
been reached among countries involved on how the fund should be
structured to help countries suffering economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo disclosed
earlier that progress made at the Manila meeting will serve as
valuable inputs to the APEC leaders when they meet in Vancouver,
Canada, on November 24-25 and discuss the Asian currency
situation.
</P>
<P>
Framework proposed at the Manila meeting can also be discussed
at the informal ASEAN finance ministers' meeting in Kuala Lumpur
on December 1 and the Asian finance ministers' meeting on December
2, he said.
</P>
<P>
If agreed by the ministers, de Ocampo said, such framework
could be presented to the ASEAN leaders' meeting in Kuala Lumpur
on December 15-16 for their approval.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres: Netanyahu's Policy Illogical, Foolish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli prime minister
Shimon Peres today described the current Likud government's policy
of putting the security issue before peace as being "illogical"
and "foolish."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Peres said Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has failed to keep the commitment
to the Oslo peace accords Israel signed with the Palestinians four
years ago, resulting in "tremendous problems" in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Peres, a member of the Knesset (parliament) of the left Labor
Party, said the security-for-peace policy has proved a failure.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of the land-for-peace formula, which
was the basis of the progress achieved in the peace process during
the previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed optimism that "there will be a change" in the
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Peace carries costs, and expensive ones," and "there is no
free peace," he said, adding that Yitzhak Rabin sacrificed his
life as the cost for peace.
</P>
<P>
Rabin, former Israeli Labor prime minister who spearheaded with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat the Oslo accords, was
assassinated by a radical Jewish youth in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Peres is here to attend the three-day fourth Middle East and
North Africa economic conference which opened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the conference, saying it is a good
opportunity to advance the peace process through regional economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
