<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, U.S. Sign Economic Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub
Khan signed three agreements on economic cooperation between the
two countries here today.
</P>
<P>
Under one agreement, the U.S. side agreed to restore the
facilities of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC),
which provides political risk insurance and some finance for U.S.
investments abroad, for Pakistan, said a press release issued
after the signing ceremony held here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC had operated in Pakistan until 1993 when the U.S.
ceased all government-to-government assistance to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Under another agreement, the U.S. would make 10 million U.S.
dollars available for Pakistan to import U.S. soybeans, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are making efforts to negotiate a bilateral
agreement on agricultural development projects, it said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the U.S. is to provide an additional 10 million U.S.
dollars to continue its aid to Pakistan through non-governmental
organizations in certain areas of humanitarian concern such as
nutrition, mother and child health, the release said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
