<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Electrified Railway Mileage Exceeds 10,000 Kilometers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The combined length of China's
electrified railways now exceeds 10,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The figure now stands at 10,514 kilometers, accounting for 18
percent of the aggregate length of the country's railway lines,
ranking the eighth in the world, according to statistics from the
Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
The ministry says that, at present, the country has 23
electrified rail lines, including some 3,870 kilometers of
double-track lines.
</P>
<P>
China began building electrified railways at the end of the
1950s. The first electrified railway, the Baoji-Chengdu line, was
completed in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Until it started the opening-up and reform drive in the late
1970s, the country had only 1,033 kilometers of electrified
railways in operation. But by early this year, the figure jumped
to 9,480 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Electrification is an important symbol of railway
modernization. After being electrified, railways can be managed in
a more efficient way, officials said, providing better conditions
for train transport.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
