<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Inspects Scene of Deadly Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak paid an inspection tour this morning to the southern
archeological resort of Luxor where a bloody terrorist attack
claimed the lives of more than 60 tourists and Egyptians Monday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and ministers of defense,
information and culture accompanied the president to Luxor, about
500 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of interior and health flew to the scene immediately
after gunmen fired randomly at tourists arriving in buses and
fought a two-hour gun battle with the police near the ruins of an
ancient temple on the west bank of the Nile.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-year-old Hatshepsut Temple, the scene of Egypt's
worst terrorist shooting rampage, last month served as the
backdrop of performances of Verdi's Opera Aida, a glittering
fanfare that had attracted thousands of visitors including
Mubarak and many world dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
Up to this morning, 64 people have been killed, including 60
international tourists from Europe, Asia and Latin America. Three
Egyptian security guards and a tourist guide were also among the
dead.
</P>
<P>
The 25 injured include 12 Swiss, two Germans, two Japanese and
one French as well as eight Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
There is still no claim of responsibility but Islamic
militants were suspected of masterminding Egypt's single largest
terrorist crime that targeted tourism, a key foreign currency
earner.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Mamdouh el-Beltagui, who is in London
attending a travel fair, said Monday that Egypt is "not less safe
than any destination" and described the crime as "something you
cannot prevent."
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militants have been leading a violent campaign to
overthrow the Egyptian secular government since 1992. Nearly
1,300 have been killed, mostly policemen and militants but the
violence has been largely confined to the south.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the government has used massive arrests,
military trials and executions to stamp the militant wave.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack targeting foreign tourists, nine
Germans and an Egyptian drive were killed on September 18 in a
gunshoot and firebomb attack on a bus in front of the Egyptian
Antiquities Museum in Cairo. The two assailants were sentenced to
death on October 30.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, a prime target of terrorism, brought about 4 million
tourists and 3 billion U.S. dollars to Egypt last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
