<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Non-Traditional Exports to Reach $456m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's non-traditional
exports (NTES) are expected to reach 456 million U.S. Dollars by
the year 2000, according to a weekly newspaper published today.
</P>
<P>
The initial target figure for the year 2000 is 200 million
dollars, Financial Times said, but this has since been increased
after the target was attained three years before the actual time
frame.
</P>
<P>
The Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) indicated that NTES will grow
to 345 million dollars by the end of 1998 and further rise to 395
million dollars by 1999, with the final goal of 456 million
dollars at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
However, the newspaper quoted EBZ director Mwansa Musonda as
saying earlier at a State House press briefing that while NTES
are poised for further growth, this requires investments in the
productive capacities especially in the agro-based products and
agro-processing.
</P>
<P>
The EBZ director added that Zambia's NTES reached above 242.5
million dollars last year, representing about a quarter of the
country's overall export earnings.
</P>
<P>
EBZ has projected a figure of 297 million dollars in NTES for
1997, but it now appears that the figure may be exceeded by the
year end.
</P>
<P>
NTES are contributing significantly to Zambia's total foreign
exchange earnings rising from eight percent in 1990 to 24.3
percent in 1996, said Musonda.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's total export earnings this year, including copper
earnings, the country's biggest traditional foreign exchange
earner, are reported to have reached above.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Zambia's imports has declined by 8.6
percent compared to the same period in 1996 because of a 10
percent decline in imports of non-oil commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to See Stable Shilling Before Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Shilling is expected
to remain stable in the 60 to 65 range against the U.S. Dollar
before the general elections, local reports today quoted Central
Bank of Kenya Governor Micah Cheserem as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I am optimistic. The Shilling is doing okey. I expect it to
trade in the 60 to 65 corridor against the Dollar in the lead-up
to the general election," Cheserem said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said he was particularly encouraged by politicians --
including President Daniel arap Moi and opposition presidential
candidates -- who have all spoken out publicly against violence
during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
"Only violence in this period could hurt the Shilling. But in
the absence of that, the Shilling is steady and can only
strengthen," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders are behaving in a honorable way and I think the
worst is well behind us," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling opened at a commercial mean rate of 63.73 to the
Dollar Monday, according to the Central Bank figures.
</P>
<P>
Early last week, the Shilling fell against all hard currencies
as the market reacted negatively to the announcement of the
election date. It slipped to as low as 65.50 against the Dollar
from the 63.50 to 64 range where it had stuck for weeks.
</P>
<P>
But with supply outweighing demand and domestic interbank
interest rates around 28 percent, the Shilling recovered from
some of those losses, opening at 63.73 on the Dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling plunged to as low as 70 against the Dollar after
a decision in July by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
stop a 205-million-Dollar three-year aid package to reinforce its
protest against corruption and governance issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
