<HEADLINE> 8th China-US Joint Commission Meeting Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth China-U.S. Joint
Commission Meeting on Science and Technology Cooperation was held
in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was presided over by Song Jian, Chinese state
councilor and minister in charge of the State Sciences and
Technology Commission, and John Gibbons, science adviser to
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The participants hailed the recent successful visit to the
United States by Chinese President Jiang Zemin, and the positive
comments by the two presidents on achievements on science and
technology cooperation between the two countries, as well as the
importance of such cooperation for bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the participants discussed strategy for
Sino-U.S. cooperation in the 21st century and the two sides agreed
to further expand the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides also conducted in-depth discussions
on cooperation in the fields of energy and environmental
protection, monitoring the Earth from outer space, control of
natural calamities, management and utilization of water resources,
agriculture and industrial technology.
</P>
<P>
Song and Gibbons signed a joint communique at the end of the
meeting, while the relevant departments of the two countries also
signed agreements on cooperation in industrial technology and
information on science and technology, as well as appendices on
cooperation in the fields of electrical automotive and terrestrial
heat.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese state councilor and the U.S. delegation will visit
Shandong and Guangdong provinces, mainly to inspect the energy,
environmental protection and science and technology projects
discussed during the recent Sino-U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation arrived in Beijing on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
