<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Surge in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Pressure for rising interest
rates continued last month as the market remained volatile due to
uncertainty over the election, according to the November issue of
the Economic Review monthly by the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Principal money market interest rates rose in September and
October following an increase in governmental demand for domestic
credit due to shortfalls in external financing of the budget
deficit, said the review.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall emerged after the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) cut its 205-million-U.S.-Dollar three-year aid package on
July 31 in a bid to reinforce protest against corruption and
governance issues in the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The yields on Treasury bills have since shot up from an
average of 19.7 percent in August to 26.2 percent in September
and stabilized at 27.2 percent last month, said the review.
</P>
<P>
High Treasury bill yields necessitated a number of policy
measures and market responses in the three months to October,
among them a shift from deposit holdings to holdings of Treasury
bills and bonds with a distinct slowdown in money supply
expansion.
</P>
<P>
The shift from deposits to government securities created a
squeeze on the banks leading to a rise in the interbank interest
rate from 17.6 percent in August to 26.9 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
The average overdraft interest rate, which is the dominant
cost of investable funds, rose from 27.4 percent in August to 28
percent in September while the average three-month deposit
interest rose from 16.8 percent in August to 18.3 percent in
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0217 </DOCNO>
