<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation May Go Uncontrolled in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's 15 percent inflation
target by the end of the year may not be achieved, and the actual
rate could be in the range of 22 to 25 percent, Citibank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its latest issue of the Citibank Treasury
Letter that it is unlikely that further drops in inflation will
be recorded in the last two months of this year.
</P>
<P>
"We therefore continue to hold the view that the 15 percent
year-end target is unachievable and the actual rate of the
Consumer Price Index will be 22 to 25 percent," said the new
letter.
</P>
<P>
It said the annual rate of inflation has been declining
progressively for the last nine months due to tight monetary
policy pursued by the Bank of Zambia, abundant fresh good
products and the stability in the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
However, all these factors have started moving in the
direction not likely to support further drops in the level of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
"Available broad money supply data shows a five percent
growth. Availability of fresh food products has declined due to
seasonal factors, while pressure in the foreign exchange market
has increased volatility and depreciation in the value of local
currency," said the bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that pressure in the supply of fresh food
products will continue until the next harvest, and maize imports
are likely to lead to higher prices as a consequence of the
expected depreciation in the value of the local currency.
</P>
<P>
This will in turn exert more pressure on the exchange markets
leading to further currency depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Last year the country recorded a 35 percent inflation rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
