<HEADLINE> Retired Mandela to Continue ANC Work: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will step down as leader of the African National
Congress (ANC) next month, an ANC spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Ronnie Mamoepa, ANC's spokesman, said that Mandela will
almost certainly continue working for the party.
</P>
<P>
Mandela,79,has been president of the ANC since 1991. He became
South Africa's first black president after all-race democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He has said repeatedly he won't run for re-election to his
party post at next month's ANC national congress or seek a second
term as state president in the next national elections in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the ANC will ask Mandela to continue working for it after
he steps down, Mamoepa was quoted by local media as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A person of president Mandela's expertise, knowledge, wisdom
and leadership qualities may have to continue to serve in the
organization," Mamoepa said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy state president Thabo Mbeki, who is also deputy
president of the ANC,is the only nominee so far to replace
Mandela as party leader, Mamoepa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
