<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Urges to Observe Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has stressed the importance of abiding by laws of the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech to the whole nation Monday night,
Khatami said that the most important responsibility he shoulders
as president is the enforcement of the constitution except in the
areas directly related to Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
He said that the national government should be organized
according to law and that all its departments should comply with
laws.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the judiciary, the legislature, and agencies
related to intelligence, security, law enforcement, culture and
economy to function within the limits of law.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noted that Khatami's speech was a response to
the political chaos among factions triggered by the presidential
elections in May.
</P>
<P>
Different groups have been trading accusations against each
other, and some even resorted to violence against others.
</P>
<P>
Khatami announced in his speech that a special body would be
set up to oversee the implementation of the constitution and find
out loopholes in law enforcement in a bid to avoid abuse or
violation of laws.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his promise to offer more freedom to the people
during the presidential election campaigns, Khatami stressed that
freedom should be based on law, and that differences of opinion
should be resolved through exchange of views.
</P>
<P>
He rejected imposition of views on others in the name of
defending the people and their freedom or in the name of Islam
and its sanctity.
</P>
<P>
Such practices should be condemned and considered as
violations of laws and obstacles to social progress, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Quality Education in Primary, Middle Schools (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- China will challenge
examination-oriented education, which is widely applied in schools
across the country, by speeding up reforms of the admission system.
</P>
<P>
This reform will be one of the 10 measures raised by the State
Education Commission (SEC) in its latest curricular.
</P>
<P>
The SEC promised that it would organize experts and experienced
teachers to revise part of the curriculum and textbooks in the
near future to cope with the demand of more quality-oriented
schools.
</P>
<P>
In places where the nine-year compulsory education is
implemented, primary school students must be accepted without
taking any entrance exam at the middle school which is nearest to
their homes, according to the SEC circular.
</P>
<P>
The exam results will no longer play a key role in evaluating
the quality of schooling and work of the teachers. The SEC asks
primary school teachers to give positive and encouraging comments
on the students' behavior and conduct, and evaluate the students'
work with degrees instead of specific scores.
</P>
<P>
In most primary and middle schools in China, teachers will
still write some comments on students' behavior at school at least
once a semester. The comments, often written in a critical way,
sometimes intensifies their relations with students and their
parents.
</P>
<P>
The unified entrance examination to college or university, a
fateful exam in China, will also face reform because of its use as
a barometer by middle schools and primary schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Meeting on Malaria, Kalaazar Held in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A three-day regional meeting of
South Asian countries on malaria and kalaazar began today in the
Bangladeshi capital of Dhaka to discuss ways for better control of
the diseases.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, sponsored by the World Health Organization's
Southeast Asia Region Office, is being attended by more than 25
specialists from Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to achieve better and more successful control
of malaria and kalaazar though improved coordination and
communication among health authorities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being held in the backdrop of an alarming
upsurge in malaria cases in a number of districts along the
northeastern and south-eastern borders of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that some 1.2 million malaria cases occur in
Bangladesh every year, most of which in 13 forest and hill
districts in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, public health administrators and disease
specialists from the four countries will share their experiences
on malaria control and review the status of joint action plans.
They are expected to lay emphasis on exchange of information and
synchronization of control operations of malaria and kalaazar in
border areas, especially during epidemic outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
In Bangladesh, a revised malaria control strategy has been in
operation since 1995, aiming to significantly reduce mortality and
morbidity among affected population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Quality Education in Primary, Middle Schools (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The national examination, restored two decades ago at the
proposal of late Chinese Leader Deng Xiaoping, has widely kindled
and increased the enthusiasm of the Chinese people for knowledge
after 10 years of dangling during the Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976). The exam was regarded as the most fair opportunity
available to almost everyone.
</P>
<P>
However, the exam has become contentious because of pressure
brought on school leaders, students and parents. School education
has become more exam-oriented instead of quality-oriented, leading
educators to work out some reform measures.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of the college entrance exam, students and their
parents pick good schools which are well-equipped and have
experienced teachers. Those weak schools, which are less
well-equipped or have less-experienced teachers, are not as
attractive to students as the good ones.
</P>
<P>
Another of the 10 measures is that the SEC will help weak
schools become stronger with better equipment and good teachers.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include training qualified and competent school
principals and teachers, encouraging teaching ethics and
strengthening study on education so as to answer practical
questions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the SEC asked local governments to help create a
loose environment for, and local schools to abide by, relevant
laws and rules to implement quality-oriented education.
</P>
<P>
The SEC also asked cooperation from parents and communities.
Earlier reports said that some parents were worried when their
children did not bring back much homework. They believed that
children were diligent only when they were busy doing their home
assignments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
