<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Cuts Budget for Veterans Payout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Finance Minister
Herbert Murerwa last night cut recurrent expenditure for all
ministries by 900 million Zimbabwe Dollars (64 million U.S.
Dollars) to finance the billion dollar gratuity payout for former
freedom veterans.
</P>
<P>
Capital budget will also be cut by 200 million Zimbabwe
Dollars (14 million U.S. Dollars), he said, adding that the
government will raise about two billion Zimbabwean Dollars 140
U.S. Dollars) from the market and take additional revenue
measures to pay 70,000 fighters' gratuities.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said, "I have had to revise the budget in the last few
weeks following the settlement with war veterans. I can now
confirm that, at the very maximum, we will require four billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (about 280 million U.S. Dollars) to finance this
scheme."
</P>
<P>
"I will also adjust certain revenue heads, which, while
painful, will not have too negative an effect on the economy
generally, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Details of these measures would be announced shortly, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added the International Monetary Fund is expected
to recommend the release of balance of payments support from
various donors following the successful conclusion of
negotiations with the Zimbabwe government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
