<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coetzer Beaten, Spirlea, Pierce Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South African Amanda Coetzer
dropped out of the two-million U.S. dollars Chase Championships
here on Monday, while Mary Pierce and Irina Spirlea defeated
their first-round opponents at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
The world No.3 Coetzer was upset 6-3, 6-3 by Nathalie Tauziat
of France. Pierce of France edged Belgium's Sabine Appelmans
6-3, 6-4 while Spirlea of Romania beat Sandrine Testud of France
6-3, 5-7, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Coetzer, who had a 100 percent match record in three meetings
with Steffi Graf this year and clinched one of the four victories
over Martina Hingis, was kept running on Tauziat's combination of
angled baseliners and precise drops.
</P>
<P>
Tauziat stepped into the court with a powerful start by
winning the first three games and ensured the opening set.
</P>
<P>
Coetzer came back a little at 2-0 but swerved again to watch
Tauziat through. Tauziat will play either No.6 Iva Majoli of
Croatia or Germany's Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
The seventh-seeded Pierce put on her best form to take
Appelmans, giving much more than the Belgian could handle.
</P>
<P>
The French pulled out of last week's Advanta Championships due
to a kidney infection.
</P>
<P>
Her quarter-final opponent will be the winner of Tuesday's
match between Hingis and Brenda Schultz-McCarthy of the
Netherlands. Spirlea set up a clash with either third-seeded
Lindsay Davenport or another American Mary Joe Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
In Monday's only doubles, Gigi Fernandez finished her career
with a bad ending.
</P>
<P>
Helena Sukova and Larisa Neiland overpowered top-seeded team
of Gigi Fernandez and Natasha Zvereva 7-5, 3-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
"It's the right time," Fernandez said when she announced this
would be her last tournament. "I'll be 34 in February. Life
changes, there's different priorities."
</P>
<P>
Fernandez won 14 Grand Slam tournament titles including French
Open and Wimbledon this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pension Fund Seminar Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- An international seminar on
the management of China's pension fund was held here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Chinese government officials and pension experts
from China, Singapore and the United States attended the meeting,
which was co-sponsored by the China State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy (SCRE) and the John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Topics for the seminar included the development of a global
capital market and pension fund system, as well as the investment,
operation and management of China's pension fund.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed that China is making great efforts to
establish a perfect pension system and, with economic development,
such a system will bring more benefits to China's financial market
and the development of the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
SCRE and John Hancock have been working in cooperation recently
on researching the management of pension fund organizations in
eastern, central and western China. The research group will come
up with proposals for new principles of pension fund management.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1862, John Hancock is one of the largest life
insurance companies in the world. It has set up representative
offices in Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
