<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is No Enemy: Schlesinger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. defense secretary
James Schlesinger today said U.S.-China ties are critical and
Americans should avoid exaggerations about China's military
capability.
</P>
<P>
Schlesinger, who spoke here tonight on "Is China a Threat to
American Security and Interests," a function organized by the
National Committee on U.S.-China Relations, said any attempt to
make China a foe "is simply partisan politics."
</P>
<P>
"U.S.-China relationship is a critical relationship, if it is
good, Asia will prosper, Asia will be pretty much at peace, if
there is suspicion and hostility, it will disrupt the region,
disrupt Asia's economic growth, Asia will be unstable and the
whole world will be somewhat unsettled," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-China relationship, he said, should be based on a
strategic understanding on both sides, instead of just attaching
economic importance to the relationship.
</P>
<P>
"For the moment China is only focusing on economic growth as a
reflection of Deng Xiaoping thought," he told an audience of more
than 100 at a downtown Manhattan hotel.
</P>
<P>
China's military equipment are outdated and even its military
expenditure is expected to grow along with its economic growth, it
still "has a long long way to go before it is in a position to
challenge U.S. forces," Schlesinger said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important for us to avoid exaggerations about even the
prospective Chinese military threat," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"China is not the enemy, there is not going to be a new cold
war," he went on.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad as saying
that "when you keep referring to a country as a future enemy, it
will not be a future enemy, but an enemy today," he asserted: "we
turn to treat China as an enemy, we should know that no one will
follow us...we will be alone."
</P>
<P>
"We can not presuppose that China will turn hostile based on
very little evidence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Currently as a board member of the National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations and senior advisor to Lehman Brothers,
Schlesinger has held three cabinet-level positions in the national
security realm. He served as the secretary of defense between
1973-75 and as the secretary of energy from 1977 to 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public to Have Say on Parliament Site: ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The ruling African
National Congress (ANC) said Monday that the public would have a
say on whether parliament should be relocated from Cape Town,
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
ANC spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa told a news conference that
although the party's policy-making National Executive Committee
(NEC) had deliberated on the matter at the weekend, it had not
reached a decision on the issue because it felt that the matter
had to involve the public.
</P>
<P>
"The NEC felt that the matter of the relocation of parliament
is of such national importance that it should be dealt with in a
rational manner through open and honest debate among the public.
</P>
<P>
"The NEC has charged the extended National Working Committee
(NWC) to make concrete proposals for such a public process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The NEC met at the weekend to consider recommendations
submitted by a three-men committee set up to investigate the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Although the NEC had earlier said the relocation issue had to
be decided before the end of this year, there was now no specific
deadline when the matter would be finalized.
</P>
<P>
The NWC needed to be given time to accomplish its task and
work out how it could best engage the public in the debate.
</P>
<P>
The matter would therefore not be discussed as expected at the
party's coming national conference in mid-December in Mafikeng,
North-West province.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey released last week, the majority of
urban South Africans want parliament to stay in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey showed that 54 percent of the polled
support Cape Town as the site for parliament, only 17 percent opt
for Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has three capitals: Pretoria (executive), Cape
Town (legislative) and Bloemfontein (judicial).
</P>
<P>
There were proposals that parliament be moved to Pretoria to
save time and money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
