<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Balance of Payments Seen to Turn Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's balance of payments
(BOP), which suffered a deficit of 127 million U.S. dollars in
fiscal 1996-97, is expected to turn around and see a surplus of
216 million dollars in the current fiscal year provided exports
register the projected growth over imports, an official document
said today.
</P>
<P>
The current projection of the BOP for 1997-98 shows a 13.2
percent increase in exports against a 12.6 percent increase in
imports, the document said, adding that this modest growth of
exports over imports will reduce the gap in merchandise trade.
</P>
<P>
Exports in fiscal 1997-98 were projected to fetch 5 billion
dollars, 13.2 percent higher than the estimated 4.418 billion
dollars in fiscal 1996-97. This growth was projected on the basis
of a robust growth of 28.8 percent of knitwear products and a
continuous growth of ready-made garments at 11.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports in 1997-98 were projected to increase by 12.6 percent
to 8.015 billion dollars from 7.120 billion dollars in fiscal
1996-97, the document said. The expected increase is due to
continuous demand for investment goods, industrial raw materials
and consumer items.
</P>
<P>
Imports of food grains are likely to take the major share,
increasing by 27.8 percent from 180 million dollars in 1996-97 to
230 million dollars this fiscal year, while non-food imports are
also projected to grow 11.8 percent over the previous year to 7.31
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit, estimated at 3.015 billion dollars, is expected
to be partly offset by a projected increase of 14.9 percent in
private transfers -- mainly remittances from workers working
abroad -- from 1.77 billion dollars in 1996-97 to 2.033 billion
dollars in 1997-98, the document said.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit, which was 902 million dollars last
year, is expected to reach 1.032 billion dollars this year, the
document added.
</P>
<P>
The document stated that the government believes that the
current account deficit, though higher than that of the previous
year, is less than 3 percent of gross domestic product and within
the sustainable limit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
