<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Continues to Shrink in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Trade deficit in the
Philippines has shrunk to 8.298 billion U.S. dollars in the first
nine months this year due to robust exports and sluggish imports,
the National Statistics Office (NSO) said today.
</P>
<P>
This represents an almost 10 percent drop from the year-ago
level of 9.212 billion dollars, the NSO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
During the nine-month period, exports increased by 23 percent
to 18.363 billion dollars from 14.926 billion dollars in the same
period of last year, while imports grew by 10.5 percent to 26.661
billion dollars from 24.138 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total trade value for the first nine months of the year
increased by 15.3 percent to 45.023 billion dollars, the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
For the month of September alone, exports posted a 24.6 percent
increase to a total of 2.337 billion dollars as imports payments
were registered at 2.875 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the NSO, electronics and components were at the
top of the list of imported goods, followed by telecommunications
equipment, electrical machinery, and industrial machinery and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and Singapore remained as the
Philippines' top markets for both imports and exports, the NSO
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
