<HEADLINE> Another Foreign Priest Kidnapped in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Four heavily armed men,
believed to be former Muslim rebels, today abducted a Belgian
Catholic priest in front of a church in the southern Philippines,
police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said father Bernard Maes, 53, was taken hostage in
Marawi City, Lanao Del Sur province, by former guerrillas of the
defunct major rebel group, the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF).
</P>
<P>
The MNLF signed a final peace agreement with the government in
September 1996. Manila promised to develop livelihood programs to
help those former rebels integrate into the civilian society.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the abductors were asking for cash benefits
being promised by the government to all rebel returnees in
exchange for Maes' release.
</P>
<P>
Maes was the second foreign priest kidnapped in the southern
Philippines. Earlier, an Irish priest was taken hostage by former
MNLF rebels and was released just recently.  
</P>
