<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Could Make Caves Hot Tourist Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A string of beautiful but
rarely seen limestone caves in southwestern China province could
become a tourist attraction with the completion of a
trans-regional railway next month.
</P>
<P>
The grouping of caves, including nine large ones and numerous
small ones, extend a dozen miles into Longan County in the
southwestern part of Guizhou Province. The caves have waterfalls,
warm springs, underground rivers and a large underground chamber
measuring 1.6 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The caves were first discovered in 1986 by a group of British
geologists. With information obtained from satellites, they
ventured twice into the then unknown caves and concluded that they
might be the most densely grouped limestone caves in the world.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, explorers and scholars from countries such as
Japan, Switzerland, Norway, Canada, the Netherlands and
New Zealand have explored the relatively unknown caves.
</P>
<P>
Connected to the outside world by a bumpy road, the caves have
not been developed as a tourist attraction to help the local
economy as officials had expected.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the Nanning-Kunming railway line that is
scheduled to open early next month can bring tourists directly to
the attraction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
