<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Tries to Calm Foreign Exchange Mart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
(RBZ) has increased the rediscount rate by three percent and
should offload all corporate Foreign Currency Account (FCA)
balances onto the foreign exchange market to support the weak
Zimbabwean Dollar.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference last night called to clear the confusion
in the market, Minister of Finance Herbert Murerwa said effective
and decisive measures had to be taken to restore order on the
foreign exchange market following last Friday's crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar plunged to an all-time low last Friday
after coming under heavy pressure from import demand. The central
bank had to pump in some 20 million U.S. dollars to support the
Zimbabwean currency.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean currency nosedived to an all-time low last week,
trading between 19 and 25 Zimbabwe Dollars to one U.S. Dollar
after speculations that the RBZ did not have sufficient foreign
currency reserves to finance import obligations among other
things.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Dollar is now trading at between 13 and 14 to the
U.S. Dollar after the RBZ rescue.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said in view of the speculative trading on the
Zimbabwean Dollar which led to last Friday's crisis it was
necessary to increase the rediscount rate.
</P>
<P>
The rate rose from 25.5 percent to 28.5 percent to help halt
the dollar's downward slide.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the rediscount rate could be increased again
if the speculative behaviors continued.
</P>
<P>
Monday's increase will result in interest rates rising,
further putting pressure on businesses.
</P>
<P>
Some 160 million U.S. Dollars are being released onto the
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
