<HEADLINE> Terracotta Horses, Warriors Under Well Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Scientists and archeologists say
they have found effective ways to protect cultural relics in the
pits at the site of the "Terra Cotta Horses and Warriors."
</P>
<P>
Located more than 30 kilometers to the east of Xi'an, capital
of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, the pits were first
discovered in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have found nearly 8,000 porcelain horses and
warriors buried in the three pits so far unearthed.
</P>
<P>
However, some of the colored drawings of the porcelain horses
and warriors have begun to roll up or peel off, and earthen
partition walls separating horses and warriors have been damaged
by changes in humidity.
</P>
<P>
To solve these problems, the museum housing the terra cotta
horses and warriors has established a team to carry out research
on protective measures for the relics, with the help of the state
and Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The museum also has imported advanced instruments and equipment
to speed up research.
</P>
<P>
The research group evaluated the elements used in the colored
drawings and then developed aqueous reinforcing solutions for the
remaining colored drawings.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the problem of the earthen partition walls,
researchers used steel plates and reinforcing piles.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also have made progress in protecting the terra
cotta treasures against such threats as earthquakes, climate
changes inside the pits and environmental quality around the
pits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
