<HEADLINE> OPEC to Discuss Oil Quota, Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A rise in both the quota and
price of crude oil is likely to be a crucial topic at an OPEC
meeting to be held here from November 26 to December 1,
Organizing Committee officials said.
</P>
<P>
While some members want a quota increase, others do not,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
As for price increase, it will depend mostly on demand. While
oil demand in Europe increased, Asian demand remained unchanged
due to the recent monetary crisis in the region, they added.
</P>
<P>
"The conference will discuss routine agenda items,
administration and finance, restructuring of the organization,
preparation for the conference of parties in Kyoto, Japan, oil
price development and monitoring of production of member
countries," Director General of Indonesian Oil and Natural Gas
Company Soepraptono Soelaiman said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the meeting will determine new quotas and elect a
new secretary general for the next three-year term. The present
secretary general is Rilwanu Lukman from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Former OPEC Secretary General Subroto from Indonesia said on
Monday that in its efforts to stabilize oil prices, the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) has always
made an approach to non-OPEC oil producing countries, particularly
those around the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
Subroto admitted that at present, OPEC contributes the smaller
portion to the world market, producing 30 million barrels of oil
per day as against 46 million barrels per day by non-OPEC
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Subroto said, of the nearly 1 billion barrels oil
reserves in the world, 77 percent are from OPEC member countries
while only 33 percent are held by non-OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
OPEC is a permanent, inter-governmental organization created in
Baghdad, Iraq, in September 1960, by Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Saudi
Arabia and Venezuela. The founding members were later joined by
Qatar, Indonesia, Libya, the United Arab Emirates, Algeria,
Nigeria, Ecuador and Gabon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
