<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Touches 21-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee touched a
21-month low of 36.89 rupees per U.S. dollar on Monday despite the
intervention of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in both the spot
and forwards markets, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Thus the Indian currency has depreciated by 2 percent over a
span of three weeks.
</P>
<P>
On October 26, the rupee closed at 36.15/19 against the U.S.
dollar and subsequently went on a roller-roaster ride to lose
nearly 75 paise (0.75 rupees).
</P>
<P>
The RBI, the central bank, pumped in an estimated 150 million
to 200 million dollars on Monday to stem the volatility in the
market.
</P>
<P>
There is no perceptible change in the RBI stance vis-a-vis the
rupee, sources here said. The central bank will allow the market
forces to determine the value of the rupee and intervene only to
rein in the volatility, they added.
</P>
<P>
"Insufficient intervention by the Reserve Bank led the rupee to
weaken to a new low," a dealer in a private sector bank commented.
</P>
<P>
Some treasury heads of Indian corporations also pointed out
that a certain degree of political instability in the country was
leading the rupee to weaken. However, they were unanimous in the
view that there would not be a sharp decline in the rupee.
</P>
<P>
"There is no panic in the market. It is the corporate demand
which has triggered the fall," the treasury head of a leading
Indian corporation said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
