<HEADLINE> 10-Month Auto Sales Drop 30 Percent in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Automobile sales in Thailand
totaled 335,203 units during January-October this year, down 30.6
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics by Toyota Motor (Thailand)
Co., almost all auto makers and dealers saw a decline in their
sales in Thailand, except Honda and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
Toyota maintained a lead in auto sales in Thailand, selling
98,406 units during the 10 months, but the number was 26.4 percent
lower than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Isuzu ranked second with sales of 76,228 units during the
period, which were down 24.1 percent year on year.
</P>
<P>
Nissan was in third place with sales of 40,156 vehicles, down
48.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Honda, which ranked fourth, sold 34,463 autos and
secured a 1.9-percent year-on-year increase.
</P>
<P>
Japanese auto sales totaled 305,576 units during the 10 months,
dropping 30.9 percent year on year.
</P>
<P>
Among European and American autos, Mercedes Benz recorded sales
of 5,979 units in the period while Ford sold 3,353 units and
Chrysler 3,078 units.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes Benz saw an 8.6-percent year-on-year drop in its sales
and Ford a 20.9-percent decline, but Chrysler posted a
year-on-year increase of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korean auto maker Hyundai sold 2,853 vehicles
in Thailand during January-October, down 31.2 percent from a year
earlier and Daewoo recorded a 48.9-percent drop with 1,275 units
sold.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the decrease in auto sales in
Thailand to the country's ongoing economic slowdown although many
car companies had launched promotion campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Many Japanese auto companies had announced suspension of or cut
in production in their factories in Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
