<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export of Manpower Continues to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's labor export has
seen a downward trend over the past year mainly due to the
suspension of recruitment by importing countries, Bangladesh
Association of International Recruiting Agencies (BAIRA) sources
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Labor export is a major foreign exchange earner for this South
Asian country, which exports more than 1 million workers every
year. The country earned 60 billion taka (about 1.34 billion U.S.
dollars) in the 1995-96 fiscal year. From January to August this
year, Bangladeshis working abroad remitted 4.01 billion taka
(about 89.5 million dollars) back home.
</P>
<P>
Manpower export declined by 9.56 percent in August this year
compared with the same month of last fiscal year, the sources
said. In September, it fell further by 0.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
If this trend continues, the sector might witness a serious
debacle, said BAIRA Chairman Mohammed Mosharraf Hossain. "Apart
from this it would leave a negative impact on the national
economy."
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exports manpower mainly to Malaysia, Saudi Arabia
and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Citing the reasons of the decline, the sources noted that
Malaysia, where at least 200,000 Bangladeshi workers have been
working, stopped fresh recruitment for the last two years while
Korea also has not imported overseas workers including those from
Bangladesh for over a year.
</P>
<P>
The lion's share of foreign remittances comes from expatriate
Bangladeshis in Saudi Arabia where about 1 million Bangladeshis
have been working in different capacities, the sources stated. But
Saudi Arabia is also not recruiting fresh workers from Bangladesh
and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The BAIRA chairman said the government should take an urgent
initiative to explore the labor market in Taiwan, Japan, Russia,
the Commonwealth of Independent States and European countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Predicts Huge Foreign Investment in Gas Blocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investments in
the exploration and development of Bangladesh's gas fields are
expected to reach 2 billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000, Energy
Minister Nooruddin Khan said.
</P>
<P>
Khan told the official news agency BSS on Monday that the
investments are expected to come in when exploration work starts
in 20 gas blocks by 12 companies selected through competitive
bids.
</P>
<P>
The real income from the gas sector would largely depend upon
how competently "we can cash this resource," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Bangladesh has 20 trillion to 50 trillion
cubic feet of natural gas reserves and it is possible that more
would be found in further exploration.
</P>
<P>
So far, six foreign companies have already invested 150 million
dollars in the exploration of eight gas blocks. The government has
set December 15 as the deadline for completing negotiations and
signing of production sharing contracts for another 12 gas blocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
