<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak2ndadd: Pak Government-Judiciary Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 18 (Xinhua) -- The confrontation between
the government and judiciary intensified today as the National
Assembly adopted the amended contempt law, tending to give
protection to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in a case of contempt
against him in the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The new law, titled Contempt of Court (Amendment) Act, 1997,
which was passed by a simple majority in the National Assembly
just after 01:00 a.m. today, came only hours after Prime Minister
Sharif declined to tender an apology in the Supreme Court in the
contempt of court case against him.
</P>
<P>
The law, which provides for an intra-court appeal before a
"larger bench consisting of all the remaining available judges of
the court within the country," is expected to go to the Senate in
the morning, where its passage is certain.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N) led by Sharif and its
allied parties, which came to power in February this year, enjoys
a majority in both the National Assembly and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The law's passage is being seen as an attempt to preempt any
adverse Supreme Court judgment against Prime Minister Sharif and
others in a contempt of court case, which resulted from remarks
made by Sharif weeks ago during a press conference accusing Chief
Justice Sajjad Ali Shah of overstepping his authority and
undermining the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic aspect of the law is a provision that it
would cover the pending cases and shall be applicable even at the
stage of the show-cause notice proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leader and former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
opposed the bill, saying this would lead to further division of
the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
She termed the bill mala fide and all the members of her
Pakistan People's Party voiced opposition to the passage of the
amendment to the act.
</P>
<P>
Some Senior Lawyers here are of the view that the amended law
is aimed at removing anomalies in the existing law.
</P>
<P>
An anomaly in the old law was that if contempt was committed
with respect to a high court, there was room for an intra-court
appeal, but if the contempt was against the Supreme Court then the
person did not have the right of appeal -- as Prime Minister
Sharif soon realized, they said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, in an unprecedented move, Sharif appeared personally
in the Supreme Court and denied the charges that he committed
contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in Pakistan's history that an elected
prime minister appeared before the apex court.
</P>
<P>
"I have neither committed contempt of court, nor do I intend to
do that," Sharif said in his written reply to the show-cause
notice issued by the Supreme Court in the contempt of court case.
</P>
<P>
The apex court had adjourned the hearing till Tuesday but
exempted Sharif from personal appearance at the court for one day
due to a short visit by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Drug Week Launched in Albanian Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Faced with a serious problem of
high school students abusing narcotic drugs, authorities today
launched an anti-drug week in schools in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the week, many teachers and students
stressed the great harm of drug-abusing to students and expressed
their firm determination to fight drugs.
</P>
<P>
The drug problem in Albanian high schools became worse
recently. A survey of 1000 students in two high schools showed
about 30 percent were taking drugs, and 42 percent of these were
female.
</P>
<P>
The survey was made by the Albanian Youth Drug Abuse
Supervision Centre. The main drugs being taken are cocaine and
heroin, and there is reportedly a drug dealer network in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The drug abuse issue has caused great concern in the
country. Many official and civilian organizations have taken part
in anti-drug activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
