<HEADLINE> OPEC to Discuss Oil Supply Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The oil ministers of the 11
Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will
discuss quotas on crude oil supplies when they meet from November
26 to December 1, in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
There was reported to be a growing consensus among OPEC members
that the quotas be raised as cold weather in the northern
hemisphere raised oil demand.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's biggest oil producer, believed demand
for OPEC oil could be higher even than a 27.2 million barrels per
day figure it submitted to last week's meeting of OPEC planners,
compared with the present 25 million.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela sided with Saudi Arabia in forecasting a higher
demand for OPEC crude next year.
</P>
<P>
A few OPEC members were reported to have disregarded the
current quotas, bringing total OPEC oil output this October to
27.9 million barrels higher than the quotas set.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting coincides with the time the United
Nations-monitored oil-for-food deal comes up for renewal early
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
