<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Trade Deficit Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's trade deficit in
the first nine months of this year dropped by 43.44 percent to 193
billion baht (5.07 billion U.S. dollars) from the same period of
last year, according to the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the period totaled 1.202 trillion baht (31.6 billion
dollars), up by 14.6 percent over a year earlier while imports
were 1.395 trillion baht (36.7 billion dollars), up by 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports in September alone were worth 177.37 billion
baht (4.6 billion dollars) while imports totaled 172.88 billion
baht (4.5 billion dollars), resulting in a surplus of 4.49 billion
baht (118 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The baht value of exports since July has looked impressive, but
once currency depreciation is taken into account, the totals are
growing at only single-digit rates compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press reports quoted Somphol Kiatphaibul,
permanent secretary of the Commerce Ministry, as saying finance
stability and foreign-exchange rates must be looked at very
carefully when calculating export targets for next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
