<HEADLINE> Two Veteran Democrats Retiring from Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Veteran California
Representatives Vic Fazio and Ron Dellums announced plans to leave
Congress today.
</P>
<P>
Dellums, who became the Democrats' point man on the National
Security Committee, said he would resign his seat effective in
February.
</P>
<P>
Fazio, third-ranking member of the Democratic leadership who
has been mentioned as a potential White House chief of staff,
announced he would retire at the end of the term.
</P>
<P>
Both cited personal reasons for their decisions.
</P>
<P>
They brought to 14 the number of Democratic departures in
advance of next fall's elections, with others anticipated by many
party officials. Several of the departures involve districts that
are expected to be highly competitive at a time when the
Democratic Party wants to devote its resources to targeting
Republican seats rather than defending its own.
</P>
<P>
Democratic spokesman Dan Sallick said only six of the 14 are
likely to be at risk next year, far fewer than was the case at
this point in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
Republicans hold a 228-203 majority in the House, with one
independent and three vacancies. In addition, a Texas
Representative has announced plans to resign shortly.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, eight Republican legislators have announced plans to
retire from the House.
</P>
<P>
In Congress, the 55-year-old Fazio has played an insider's
role, using his seat on the Appropriations Committee over the
years to help his district as well as tending to the needs of his
colleagues in Congress.
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the caucus, he has tried to serve as a bridge
between the liberal and more moderate members of caucus.
</P>
<P>
Dellums, 62, rose through seniority to become chairman of the
House Armed Services Committee in 1993, gaining respect from
lawmakers in both parties. He lost his chairmanship after one
term when Republicans gained a majority.
</P>
<P>
He argued persistently for less military spending and more
money for social programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
