<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Stork Tower to Be Rebuilt in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Yongji, a city in Shanxi
Province, has allocated a special fund to reconstruct an ancient
stork tower named Guanquelou, which was destroyed in the Yuan
Dynasty (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
Completed in 580, the building was one of the four noted
ancient towers in China. The other three towers including
Huanghelou, Yueyangluo and Tengwangge (Yellow Crane Tower, Yueyang
Tower and Tengwang Pavilion) have been rebuilt in Hubei, Hunan and
Jiangxi provinces respectively.
</P>
<P>
Guangquelou once attracted men of letters including Tang poet
Wang Zhihuan who wrote "On the Stork Tower."
</P>
<P>
The 76-meter-high tower along the Yellow River will occupy 153
hectares and require an investment of 47 million yuan to complete.
</P>
<P>
The foundation work has been completed at a cost of 4 million
yuan, with the reconstruction scheduled for completion by
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
