<HEADLINE> Italian FM Expresses Condolences Over Luxor Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini sent today a message of condolence to his Egyptian
counterpart, Amr Moussa, over the terrorist attack in Luxor in
which at least 61 tourists were killed.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the attack as a "grave act of senseless barbarism,"
Dini said: "I wish to recognize your nation's great and courageous
efforts in the battle against terrorism as well as its support,
with all means available, of the Mideast peace process."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that only a "just and long-lasting peace" in the
entire Middle East region can "definitively defeat the forces of
hate and evil."
</P>
<P>
The attack took place near the Hatshepsut ruins when the
terrorists, believed to be Muslim extremists, opened fire on about
150 tourists who has just been dropped off by tour buses.
</P>
<P>
A gun battle with local police then followed and in the end 61
tourists, mostly Swiss, German and Japanese, were killed. This
was the bloodiest terrorist attack against tourists in Egypt and
the first in Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
