<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Position on APEC's Planned Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will urge the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum to focus on
strengthening the finance system when an APEC fund is established,
rather than on stabilizing currencies.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi revealed this stance on his first day in office at
the Commerce Ministry Monday. He will take part in the APEC
ministerial meeting in Vancouver, Canada, this weekend, according
to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said APEC's planned fund would complement the
International Monetary Fund by providing members with an
additional means of drawing up economic recovery plans.
</P>
<P>
But Thailand would suggest that the fund's role be for
strengthening the financial system and technical cooperation and
not stabilizing currencies as favored by some senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The Vancouver meeting is likely to focus on ways the APEC fund
could help financially-troubled Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said he would discuss the issue with Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai and state agencies to formulate an official position
on the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
