<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican President Confident About Financial Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is one of the
developing countries that survived the recent financial turmoil
because of its responsible economic policy, Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of a financial brokers
convention, Zedillo said it is of the utmost importance that the
country be protected from extreme financial moves in the world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, he affirmed, it is even more important that the
current economic policy -- which was implemented some 15 years ago
-- be a responsible one. Only under that condition will the
nation enjoy economic growth along with social justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
He commented that world financial conditions leave little room
for prudence and responsibility, and sometimes they are not
present at all in the world monetary market.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo asserted that mature and objective management of the
Mexican financial market has given confidence to the economy over
the last few weeks despite the difficult situations that occur in
international markets.
</P>
<P>
The President said that Mexicans do not want another financial
crisis with high punitive costs for the average people, which
occurs as a result of a low domestic savings rate and excessive
dependence on foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that his government will continue to maintain a
healthy treasury, assure political stability, lower inflation and
interest rates, and achieve a wise level of indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said the stock market will continue to be a cornerstone
of the financial system in Mexico, so that the country can
continue to make full use of foreign capital and domestic
savings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
