<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exposed Stalagmite Relics Found in Hebei Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts stumbled
upon ancient stalagmite relics exposed at a hilltop site in
Lincheng county of north China's Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
Geographers and archeologists said the find, the first of its
kind in China, is a marvelous natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
When doing field work near a cave, a group led by Song Linhua,
a professor from the Institute of Geophysics under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, ran across the 500-square meter stalagmite
ruins. The highest one was 10 meters by 2.3 meters in diameter.
</P>
<P>
Initially shaped 500 million years ago, the cave under the
stalagmite sprawl on the hill has five halls, the largest
measuring 2,470 square meters, and more than 150 scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
The recent find provides important scientific information about
the land forms of the Taihang Mountains in north China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Implement ASEAN Drug Control Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is making preparations
to act as a host in implementing ASEAN members' three-year
narcotic drug control project individually and collectively.
</P>
<P>
According to today's official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar, local medical officers are being trained on drug abuse
surveillance and substance abuse management.
</P>
<P>
The training also includes collecting data for demand reduction
as well as statistics on drug addicts to support law enforcement
bodies in demand reduction measures.
</P>
<P>
The three-year ASEAN plan, which was worked out at the 18th
meeting of ASEAN Senior Officials on Drug Matters (ASOD) in
Bangkok in 1995, covers programs on education, treatment,
rehabilitation, control, eradication and research.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar last attended the 20th meeting of the ASOD in Brunei in
August as a full-fledged member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there were 56,847 registered
addicts in Myanmar in 1996. Of them, 62 percent are opium addicts,
29 percent heroin addicts and 9 percent addicted to other drugs.
</P>
<P>
Six major drug treatment centers have been set up in the
country covering Yangon, Mandalay, Myitkyina, Taunggyi, Lashio and
Kengtung, the statistics showed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine President Plays Down Market Repercussions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President
Carlos Menem today ruled out possible negative effects upon his
country's economy during the present international financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the award ceremony of the "National Prize For
Quality, 1997," the president said: "We are enduring firmly this
international crisis." He described it as a tremendous shake for
the entire world.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide economy, especially in southeast Asia, has been
affected by a currency crisis sparked by Thailand's devaluation of
the Baht on July 2.
</P>
<P>
Menem underlined the strength shown by Argentina against this
new financial turmoil and compared it with the "Tequila effect"
triggered by the 1994-95 peso crisis in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Unlike what had happened during the peso crisis, the country's
monetary reserves this time continued increasing instead of
plunging during the weeks following the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank reported that by October 23, deposits totaled
three billion U.S. dollars while the reserves had fallen one
billion dollars. The granting of credits remained stable.
</P>
<P>
However, during the "Tequila Effect" in early 1995, about eight
billion dollars were pulled out of banks and left the country, the
bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
