<HEADLINE> Plavsic Urged to Dissolve Interior Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Deputies of the Bosnian Serb
parliament today urged the Republika Srpska (RS) President,
Biljana Plavsic, to dissolve the interior ministry established in
Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
The 45 deputies from the ruling Serbian Democratic party (SDS)
and Serbian Radical party (SRS), who met in Jahorina five days
ahead of early legislative polls, voted unanimously for a
declaration. It warned the RS president not to pursue foreign
policies, which were not approved by the Bosnian government and
the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's declaration also warned the president not to
do anything that violated the RS constitution and laws.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned "inappropriate behaviour of foreign
armed forces that went beyond their mandate and seriously
endangered order and peace... bringing them almost to occupation
status."
</P>
<P>
Deputies also raised doubts over the legality of the
parliamentary elections to be held this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The November 22-23 polls were not "scheduled legally", but
imposed by the international community on the Serb entity in
Bosnia, their declaration said.
</P>
<P>
"International pressures were encouraged by the RS president
Biljana Plavsic," who dissolved the assembly on July 3 in an
anti-constitutional move, it said.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians also said they opposed any revision of the
Dayton peace accords and any modification of the SFOR mandate.
</P>
<P>
Deputies said they remained firm on reinforcing relations
between the RS and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY), until
"final and definite unification." The RS and FRY signed a special
relations treaty in February.
</P>
<P>
In its session today, deputies refused to dissolve the
parliament, until the new mandates of those elected at the weekend
polls are verified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
