<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Chinese Know Their Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese, no matter in remote
rural areas or in a busy metropolis, all enjoy good neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted in Beijing shows that among the young
below 35, 80 percent "know all their neighbors very well" or "know
some very well but have a nodding acquaintance of the rest" or
"know all and usually say 'hello' to them."
</P>
<P>
Some analyses indicate that citizens who live in multi-story
buildings as well as in single-story homes all know their
neighbors. Eighty percent of those polled said good neighborhoods
help people understand and care about each other and give them a
stronger sense of security.
</P>
<P>
"Good neighborhoods are a tradition for the Chinese", said Zhou
Xianjin, a researcher at the Shandong Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, the survey reveals that people still have the
habit of visiting neighbors' house for casual chats.
</P>
<P>
Many cities in China now promote ethic and cultural progress,
which includes good relationships with neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
