</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived
here Monday on her 20-hour visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit by a U.S. secretary of state to
Pakistan in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Pakistan, Albright will hold talks with
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and
other senior officials on bilateral, regional and international
affairs. (Pakistan-US-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Altogether 60 people were confirmed dead and 24
injured in Egypt's largest single terrorist shooting rampage in
the Upper Egyptian city of Luxor Monday morning, the Interior
Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry issued its first words nearly nine hours after six
unidentified gunmen opened fire randomly at groups of tourists in
front of a desert tourist site and fought a two-hour gun battle
with the police near the Valley of Queens in Luxor, about 560
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-seven Swiss, German and Japanese tourists, two Egyptian
security guards and a tourist guide were among the dead.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,300 have been killed since 1992 when the Islamic
extremists launched a violent campaign to topple the secular
government led by President Hosni Mubarak. (Egypt-Tourists-Terror)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government rejected Monday an Iraqi
compromise proposal of readmitting American members of a UN arms
inspection team, saying "there is no room for negotiation."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz has reportedly proposed
to readmit the American arms inspectors if the United Nations
agreed to change the composition of the inspection groups.
</P>
<P>
Aziz noted that equal representation on the arms inspection
teams to all five permanent Security Council members would help to
resolve the current crisis. (UK-Iraq-UN) 
</P>
