<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Scientist Links Cancer With Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WARSAW, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Studies by scientists in Poland
have again linked smoking with many serious ailments such as
cancer and heart attack.
</P>
<P>
Witold Zatonski, a professor at the Warsaw Cancer Research
Center, said that when smoking a cigarette, a person inhales about
4,000 poisonous chemicals; among that number, 40 are capable of
causing cancer.
</P>
<P>
The chemicals enter the blood supply through the respiratory and
circulatory system and affect many vital organs. The process is
repeated with each cigarette, he said.
</P>
<P>
The professor also warned against the danger of second-hand
inhalation of cigarette smoke. Non-smoking wives of smokers are
more likely to suffer from cancer than non-smoking wives of
non-smokers, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
