<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statues Commemorate Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- A group of giant statues,
entitled "Catastrophe of the People," has been completed in the
Nanjing Jiangdongmen Museum here in the capital of east China's
Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
The group statues, located in the mourning square of the
museum, commemorate the event in which 300 thousand Chinese were
massacred by Japanese aggressors nearly 60 year ago.
</P>
<P>
The statues include bronze sculptures of the heads and arms of
the victims. Designed by sculptor Wu Xianlin, the two-ton head
sculpture is 2.5 meters high and 2 meters in diameter, and the
five-ton arms sculpture is 7 meters long and 2.75 meters high.
</P>
<P>
The group statues were designed by professor Qi Kang, an
architect at Southeast University.
</P>
<P>
The statues and the mourning square are part of the museum's
construction project, which is expected to be finished before
December 13 for the 60th anniversary of Nanjing Massacre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
