<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Experiment with New Tuberculosis Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 18 (Xinhua) -- China will conduct a
nationwide clinical experiment with five-month chemotherapy
treatments for Tuberculosis (TB) patients beginning Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
The experiment will be conducted by four agencies in charge of
the prevention and treatment of TB. Four types of bactericides
have been tested so far. Sixty-five percent of patients in the
test groups were negative on the sputum test at one month; 25
percent at two months; and 5 percent at the three-month mark and
after.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts also found that patients who have already
turned negative on the sputum test rarely have a relapse if given
three months of intensive treatment.
</P>
<P>
The common six-month chemotherapy period has proved successful
in many countries, especially for those TB-sufferers whose sputum
tests are positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
