<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russia Border Trade Flourishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Residents of China's
Heilongjiang Province on the Sino-Russian border traded a record
of 250 million U.S. dollars in goods with their Russian
counterparts in the first 10 months of this year, an increase of
50 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang officials attributed the growth in border trade to
the flexible nature of the trade and to preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
Compared with traditional border trade, such transactions are
characterized by small quantity, fine quality and expedited
settlement.
</P>
<P>
To encourage trade, the Chinese government early last year
introduced tariff exemptions for transactions of less than 1,000
yuan (120.48 U.S. dollars) per person per day.
</P>
<P>
More staff members have been added in commodity inspection and
market and technical supervision to ensure trade quality.
</P>
<P>
The northernmost Heilongjiang Province has a border with Russia
of more than 3,045 kilometers, along which more than 20 ports of
entry have been opened.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
