<HEADLINE> Indonesia Tells Iraq to Follow U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has called on Iraq
to abide by the U.N. Security Council's resolutions issued
following the Gulf War in 1990.
</P>
<P>
"Without complying with the resolutions, Iraq will always face
the same situation from time to time," Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
said here last night.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Indonesia has expressed its deep concern over
the worsening crisis between Iraq and the United States, offering
the hope that the crisis would not explode into a new war.
</P>
<P>
"As I stated before, Indonesia is very concerned about the
worsening situation. Indonesia still hopes there remain ways to
solve the problems through diplomatic approaches," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been bracing for possible U.S. military action
following its expulsion last Thursday of Americans working for the
U.N. special commission overseeing the disarming of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But Iraqi President Saddam Hussein said late Sunday that his
country is not looking for confrontation with the United States
and wants a solution with the U.N. Security Council "through
dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the U.N. sanctions against Iraq have so far caused
suffering for innocent people including children, women and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
"So Indonesia and other countries hope that the long-standing
conflicts can be solved as soon as possible through dialogue among
the interested parties," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
