<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ATP to Introduce New Rankings System in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- ATP Tour will introduce new
rankings system in the year of 2000 and pay more attention to
players' current performance, a leading ATP Tour official on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Larry Scott said present rules took much previous form into
account based on a complicated points system. New measure will
ensure lower-seeded upcoming players a least week-long standings
up at the top of the world rankings.
</P>
<P>
New system is part of ATP Tour plans to set up a new super
league of compulsory tournaments comprising of seven leading
events, in addition to the four Grand Slams events.
</P>
<P>
Players miss any of the 11 events will lose points while their
year-end rankings count upon performance in the compulsory league
and seven best other tournaments as well.
</P>
<P>
Discussions of the possibility of women's super league is
under way. International Tennis Federation (ITF) will also
consider the change of season-ending ATP Tour world championships
which are not taken account into rankings calculation.
</P>
<P>
The world championships will stay in Hanover in Germany until
1999. Site and format of the championships is set to be changed
after that.
</P>
<P>
Indian Wells, Key Biscayne, Stuttgart and Paris indoor
tournaments have been insured in the new league, while two
European clay events and one North American hardcourt event are
yet to be designated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
