<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Party Peace Talks Likely to Start Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Four-party peace talks for
the Korean Peninsula are likely to start in Geneva next month, a
senior U.S. State Department official said today.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said in a statement that a preparatory
meeting will be held Friday at Columbia University in New York,
which "will make arrangements" for the long-awaited Geneva
four-party peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The four parties are the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
the Republic of Korea, the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said the Geneva talks, likely starting in
the first half of next month, will involve a long, drawn-out
process.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a pretty significant thing that all four countries
at a senior level are going to go to Geneva and actually begin
what will be a very long and extended set of talks about peace on
the Korean Peninsula," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
