<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Settle Dispute With Iraq Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
today that he intended to settle the dispute with Iraq peacefully
but did not rule out any options in a diplomatic endeavor backed
by military action.
</P>
<P>
"I am trying to settle this issue peacefully. But our
diplomatic efforts must be backed by our strong military
capabilities. We cannot rule out any options," he told a meeting
at a Cessna plane factory in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not elaborate how to end the dispute, which began
last month when the U.N. Security Council approved a U.S.-British
bill to threaten new sanctions by restricting Iraqi officials from
traveling abroad, and Iraq decided to expel American inspectors in
the U.N. Special Commission, alleging they were gathering
intelligence in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Sunday proposed to end
the dispute with the United States, saying that Baghdad would
readmit American weapons inspectors if the U.N. Security Council
agreed to change the makeup of the inspection teams, with equal
representation given to each permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
But the United States flatly rejected the idea, saying Iraq had
no right to determine the composition of the U.N. weapons
inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States and Britain have discussed with
France and Russia a proposal to make "modest adjustments" to
improve the oil-for-food program for Iraq, providing Baghdad
cooperated with U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq said the deal was a "non-starter" in solving the
current dispute. It emphasized those diplomats should instead
address how sanctions, imposed in 1991, would be eased or lifted.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the inadequate inspection system for Iraq's
chemical and biological weapons programs would be as grave a
threat to world peace as the nuclear threat in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
"What they (the inspectors) are doing matters. It matters to
you, to your children and to the future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
