<DOCNO> XIE19971118.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion Occurs as Greek Students Mark Polytechnic Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- An explosion took place in the
Greek capital city of Athens today when thousands of students were
celebrating the anniversary of the 1973 uprising against the then
Greek military junta.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which was caused by a makeshift bomb made of gas
canisters, occurred outside the Greek National Economy and Finance
Ministry opposite the Athens Polytechnic, according to the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) today.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between students and policemen also happened after fire
brigade and policemen rushing to the scene were attacked by groups
of youths who threw rocks, pieces of wood and molotov cocktails.
Police returned with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of students also marched to the American embassy
while some 3,000 policemen were watching closely the development
of the march in order to prevent any further riots.
</P>
<P>
The three-day celebrations began on Saturday with the closure
of all Greek schools and Athens universities.
</P>
<P>
On November 17, 1973, at least 23 people were killed and some
400 wounded when the army loyal to Greece's dictator George
Papadopoulos stormed the Polytechnic after a three-day standoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
